ral hours after a dance by the Lena Lang Circle of the Foresters of America had concluded. It threatened to spread to the warehouse of the Bronx Drug Company, where large quantities of chemicals were stored. The structure was described as being an ''old three-story wood and stucco,\nwhich was the cradle of the careers of many politicians.'' The smoke drove\nforty-eight families in the tenement across the way, at 581 East 170th Street, to the street. Firemen of Engine Company 50, stationed on the roof,\nwet the fire down.\n\nThe building was designed by architect Louis Falk, New York architect.\n\n==References==\n*[[The New York Times]], ''Hints that M'Call Bought Judgeship'', October 22, 1913.\n*The New York Times, ''Fight at Bakers Picnic'', June 7, 1914.\n*The New York Times, ''Bullets Imperil Dancers'', December 18, 1916.\n*The New York Times, ''Fifty Fight for Coats'', November 8, 1920.\n*The New York Times, ''Trading in the Bronx'', July 7, 1922.\n*The New York Times, ''Niblos Garden in Bronx Sold'', August 5, 1922.\n*The New York Times, ''City Brevities'', July 2, 1924, Page 40.\n*The New York Times, ''Amateurs at Bronx Lyceum'', October 29, 1926, Page 26.\n*The New York Times, ''Full Shutdown of Dye Shops Voted'', February 22, 1928, Page 19.\n*The New York Times, ''Orangemen Hold Parade'', July 13, 1928, Page 11.\n*The New York Times, Flames Destroy The Bronx Lyceum'', March 4, 1929, Page 23.\n*\"''A Standard History of Freemasonry in the State of New York''\" by Peter Russ, Lewis Publishing Co., 1899, Page 258.\n{{coord|40.8349|-73.9035|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-NY|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Former buildings and structures in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Cultural history of New York City]]\n[[Category:History of the Bronx]]\n", "name_user": "TheImaCow", "label": "safe", "comment": "removedCategory:Former buildings and structures in the BronxusingHotCat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bronx_Lyceum"}
{"title_page": "Antinatalism", "text_new": "{{short description|Philosophical position that assigns a negative value to birth}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n'''Antinatalism''', or '''anti-natalism''', is a philosophical position and social movement that assigns a negative [[value (ethics)|value]] to [[birth]]. Antinatalists argue that people should abstain from procreation because it is [[morality|morally]] [[evil|bad]] (some also recognize the procreation of other [[sentience|sentient beings]] as morally bad). In scholarly and in literary writings, various [[ethics|ethical]] foundations have been presented for antinatalism.<ref>K. Akerma, ''Antinatalismus \u2013 Ein Handbuch'', epubli, 2017.</ref> Some of the earliest surviving formulations of the idea that it would be better not to have been born come from ancient Greece.<ref>W. Tatarkiewicz, ''O szcz\u0119\u015bciu'' (''On Happiness''), Warszawa: Pa\u0144stwowe Wydawnictwo Naukowe, 1979, pp. 420\u2013421.</ref> The term antinatalism is in opposition to the term [[natalism]] or pro-natalism, and was used probably for the first time as the name of the position by Belgian philosopher [[Th\u00e9ophile de Giraud]] in his book ''L'art de guillotiner les procr\u00e9ateurs: Manifeste anti-nataliste''.<ref>K. Akerma, ''Antinatalismus...'' op. cit., p. 301.</ref>\n\n== Arguments ==\n\n=== In religion ===\n\nThe teaching of the [[Buddha]], among other [[Four Noble Truths]] and the beginning of [[Khandhaka|Mah\u0101vagga]], is interpreted by [[Hari Singh Gour]] as follows:\n\n{{blockquote|Buddha states his propositions in the pedantic style of his age.  He throws them into a form of sorites; but, as such, it is logically faulty and all he wishes to convey is this:  Oblivious of the suffering to which life is subject, man begets children, and is thus the cause of old age and death.  If he would only realize what suffering he would add to by his act, he would desist from the procreation of children; and so stop the operation of old age and death.<ref>H. Singh Gour, ''The Spirit of Buddhism'', Whitefish, Montana: Kessinger Publishing, 2005, pp. 286\u2013288.</ref>}}\n\nThe [[Marcionites]] believed that the visible world is an evil creation of a crude, cruel, jealous, angry [[demiurge]], [[Yahweh]]. According to this teaching, people should oppose him, abandon his world, not create people, and trust in the good God of mercy, foreign and distant.<ref>H. Jonas, ''The Gnostic Religion: The Message of the Alien God and the Beginnings of Christianity'', Boston: Beacon Press, 1958, pp. 144\u2013145.</ref><ref>P. Karavites, ''Evil, Freedom, and the Road to Perfection in Clement of Alexandria'', Leiden: Brill, 1999, p. 94.</ref><ref>Clement of Alexandria, ''Stromateis, Books 1\u20133 (The Fathers of the Church, volume 85)'', Washington D.C.: CUA Press, 2010, pp. 263\u2013271.</ref>\n\nThe [[Encratites]] observed that birth leads to [[death]]. In order to conquer death, people should desist from procreation:  \"not produce fresh fodder for death\".<ref>P. Brown, ''The Body and Society:  Men, Women, and Sexual Renunciation in Early Christianity'', New York: Columbia University Press, 1988, p. 96.</ref><ref>G. Quispel, ''Gnostica, Judaica, Catholica:  Collected Essays of Gilles Quispel'', Leiden: Brill, 2008, p. 228.</ref><ref>Clement of Alexandria, ''Stromateis'', op. cit., pp. 295\u2013296.</ref>\n\nThe [[Manichaeans]],<ref>H. Jonas, ''The Gnostic...'', op. cit., pp. 228, 231.</ref><ref>I. Gardner and S.N.C. Lieu, ''Manichaean Texts from the Roman Empire'', New York: Cambridge University Press, 2004, pp. 7, 22.</ref><ref>S.G. Kochuthara, ''The Concept of Sexual Pleasure in the Catholic Moral Tradition'', Rome: Gregorian Biblical BookShop, 2007, p. 165.</ref> the [[Bogomils]]<ref>D. Obolensky, ''The Bogomils: A Study in Balkan Neo-Manichaeism'', New York: Cambridge University Press, 2004, p. 114.</ref><ref>F. Curta, ''Southeastern Europe in the Middle Ages, 500\u20131250'', New York: Cambridge University Press, 2006, p. 236.</ref><ref>J. Lacarri\u00e8re, ''The Gnostics'', London: Owen, 1977, p. 116.</ref> and the [[Cathars]]<ref>M.J. Fromer, ''Ethical issues in Sexuality and Reproduction'', St. Louis: Mosby, 1983, p. 110.</ref><ref>S. Runciman, ''The Medieval Manichee:  A Study of the Christian Dualist Heresy'', New York: Cambridge University Press, 1947, pp. 151\u2013152.</ref><ref>D. Elliott, ''Spiritual Marriage: Sexual Abstinence in Medieval Wedlock'', Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1995, pp. 133\u2013134.</ref> believed that procreation sentences the soul to imprisonment in evil matter. They saw procreation as an instrument of an [[Dualistic cosmology#In Christianity|evil god]], demiurge, or of [[Satan]] that imprisons the divine element in matter and thus causes the divine element to suffer.\n\n=== Theodicy and anthropodicy ===\n\n[[Julio Cabrera (philosopher)|Julio Cabrera]] considers the issue of being a creator in relation to [[theodicy]] and argues that just as it is impossible to defend the idea of a good [[God]] as creator, it is also impossible to defend the idea of a good man as creator. In parenthood, the human parent imitates the divine parent, in the sense that education could be understood as a form of pursuit of \"salvation\", the \"right path\" for a child. However, a human being could decide that it is better not to suffer at all than to suffer and be offered the later possibility of salvation from suffering. In Cabrera's opinion, evil is associated not with the [[nothing|lack of being]], but with the suffering and dying of those that are alive. So, on the contrary, evil is only and obviously associated with [[being]].<ref name=autoname1>J. Cabrera, ''Projeto de \u00c9tica Negativa'', S\u00e3o Paulo: Edic\u00f5es Mandacaru, 1989 (second edition: ''A \u00c9tica e Suas Nega\u00e7\u00f5es, N\u00e3o nascer, suic\u00eddio e pequenos assassinatos'', Rio De Janeiro: Rocco, 2011). [https://misantropiaemelancolia.wordpress.com/2017/10/24/project-of-negative-ethics/] English translation of the first chapter.</ref>\n\nKarim Akerma, due to the moral problem of man as creator, introduces anthropodicy, a twin concept for theodicy. He is of the opinion that the less faith in the Almighty Creator-God there is, the more urgent the question of anthropodicy becomes. Akerma thinks that for those who want to lead ethical lives, the causation of suffering requires a justification. Man can no longer shed responsibility for the suffering that occurs by appealing to an imaginary entity that sets moral principles. For Akerma, antinatalism is a consequence of the collapse of theodicy endeavours and the failure of attempts to establish an anthropodizee. According to him, there is no metaphysics nor moral theory that can justify the production of new people, and therefore anthropodicy is indefensible as well as theodicy.<ref name=autoname2>K. Akerma, ''Verebben der Menschheit?: Neganthropie und Anthropodizee'', Verlag Karl Alber, Freiburg im Breisgau: Verlag Karl Alber, 2000.</ref>\n\n=== Peter Wessel Zapffe ===\n\n[[Peter Wessel Zapffe]] viewed humans as a biological paradox. According to him, [[consciousness]] has become over-evolved in humans, thereby making us incapable of functioning normally like other animals: cognition gives us more than we can carry. Our frailness and insignificance in the cosmos are visible to us. We want to live, and yet because of how we have evolved, we are the only species whose members are conscious that they are destined to die. We are able to analyze the past and the future, both our situation and that of others, as well as to imagine the suffering of billions of people (as well as of other living beings) and feel [[compassion]] for their suffering. We yearn for justice and meaning in a world that lacks both. This ensures that the lives of conscious individuals are tragic. We have desires: spiritual needs which reality is unable to satisfy, and our species still exists only because we limit our awareness of what that reality actually entails. Human existence amounts to a tangled network of defense mechanisms, which can be observed both individually and socially, in our everyday behavior patterns. According to Zapffe, humanity should cease this self-deception, and the natural consequence would be its [[extinction]] by abstaining from procreation.<ref name=autoname3>P.W. Zapffe, ''The Last Messiah'', ''Philosophy Now'', 2004, number 45, pp. 35\u201339.</ref><ref>P. W. Zapffe, ''Om det tragiske'', Oslo: Pax Forlag, 1996.</ref><ref>P. W. Zapffe, H. T\u00f8nnessen, ''Jeg velger sannheten: En dialog mellom Peter Wessel Zapffe og Herman T\u00f8nnessen'', Oslo: Universitets forlaget, 1983.</ref>\n\n=== Negative ethics ===\n\nJulio Cabrera proposes a concept of \"negative ethics\" in opposition to \"affirmative\" ethics, meaning ethics that affirm [[dasein|being]].<ref name=\"autoname1\" /><ref>[http://repositorio.unb.br/bitstream/10482/17430/3/Livro_CritiqueAffirmativeMorality.pdf] J. Cabrera, ''A critique of affirmative morality (A reflection on death, birth and the value of life)'', Bras\u00edlia: Julio Cabrera Editions, 2014 (English edition). J. Cabrera, ''Cr\u00edtica de la moral afirmativa: Una reflexi\u00f3n sobre nacimiento, muerte y valor de la vida'', Barcelona: Gedisa, 1996 (original Spanish edition, second edition in 2014).</ref><ref>J. Cabrera (editor), ''\u00c9tica Negativa: problemas e discuss\u00f5es'', Goi\u00e2nia: UFG, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://repositorio.unb.br/bitstream/10482/15274/1/LIVRO_PorqueTeAmo.pdf] J. Cabrera, T. Lenharo di Santis, ''Porque te amo, N\u00e3o nascer\u00e1s!: Nascituri te salutant'', Bras\u00edlia: LGE, 2009.\n[https://misantropiaemelancolia.wordpress.com/2017/09/28/first-chapter-of-nascituri-te-salutant/] English translation.</ref><ref>J. Cabrera, ''Discomfort and Moral Impediment: The Human Situation, Radical Bioethics and Procreation'', Newcastle upon Tyne: Cambridge Scholars Publishing, 2019. [https://www.cambridgescholars.com/discomfort-and-moral-impediment] A thirty-page extract on the publisher's website. J. Cabrera, ''Mal-estar e moralidade: situa\u00e7\u00e3o humana, \u00e9tica e procria\u00e7\u00e3o respons\u00e1vel'', Bras\u00edlia: UnB, 2018 (original Portuguese edition).</ref> He describes procreation as manipulation and harm, a unilateral and non-consensual sending of a human being into a painful, dangerous and morally impeding situation.\n\nCabrera regards procreation as an [[ontology|ontological]] issue of total manipulation: one's very being is manufactured and used; in contrast to intra-worldly cases where someone is placed in a harmful situation. In the case of procreation no chance of defense against that act is even available. According to Cabrera: manipulation in procreation is visible primarily in the unilateral and non-consensual nature of the act, which makes procreation per se inevitably asymmetrical; be it a product of forethought, or a product of neglect. It is always connected with the interests (or disinterests) of other humans, not the created human. In addition, Cabrera points out that in his view the manipulation of procreation is not limited to the act of creation itself, but it is continued in the process of raising the child, during which parents gain great power over the child's life, who is shaped according to their preferences and for their satisfaction. He emphasizes that although it is not possible to avoid manipulation in procreation, it is perfectly possible to avoid procreation itself and that then no moral rule is violated.\n\nCabrera believes that the situation in which one is placed through procreation, human life, is structurally negative in that its constitutive features are inherently adverse. The most prominent of them are, according to Cabrera, the following:\n* (a) The being acquired by a human at birth is decreasing (or \"decaying\"), in the sense of a being that begins to end since its very emergence, following a single and irreversible direction of deterioration and decline, of which complete consummation can occur at any moment between some minutes and around one hundred years.\n* (b) From the moment they come into being, humans are affected by three kinds of frictions: physical pain (in the form of illnesses, accidents and natural catastrophes to which they are always exposed); discouragement (in the form of \"lacking the will\", or the \"mood\" or the \"spirit\", to continue to act, from mild taedium vitae to serious forms of depression), and finally, exposure to the aggressions of other humans (from gossip and slander to various forms of discrimination, persecution and injustice), aggressions that we too can inflict on others, also submitted, like us, to the three kinds of friction.\n* (c) To defend themselves against (a) and (b), human beings are equipped with mechanisms of creation of positive values (ethical, [[aesthetic]], [[religious]], [[entertaining]], [[recreational]], as well as values contained in human realizations of all kinds), which humans must keep constantly active. All positive values that appear within human life are reactive and palliative; they are introduced by the permanent, anxious and uncertain struggle against the decaying life and its three kinds of friction.\n\nCabrera calls the set of these characteristics A\u2013C the \"terminality of being\". He is of the opinion that a huge number of humans around the world cannot withstand this steep struggle against the terminal structure of their being, which leads to destructive consequences for them and others: [[suicide]]s, major or minor [[mental disorder|mental illnesses]], or [[aggression|aggressive behavior]]. He accepts that life may be \u2013 thanks to human's own merits and efforts \u2013 bearable and even very pleasant (though not for all, due to the phenomenon of moral impediment), but also considers it problematic to bring someone into existence so that they may attempt to make their life pleasant by struggling against the difficult and oppressive situation we place them in by procreating. It seems more reasonable, according to Cabrera, simply not to put them in that situation, since the results of their struggle are always uncertain.\n\nCabrera believes that in ethics, including affirmative ethics, there is one overarching concept which he calls the \"Minimal Ethical Articulation\", \"MEA\" (previously translated into English as \"Fundamental Ethical Articulation\" and \"FEA\"): the consideration of other people's interests, not manipulating them and not harming them. Procreation for him is an obvious violation of MEA \u2013 someone is manipulated and placed in a harmful situation as a result of that action. In his view, values included in the MEA are widely accepted by affirmative ethics, they are even their basics, and if approached [[hypocrisy|radically]], they should lead to the refusal of procreation.\n\nFor Cabrera, the worst thing in human life and by extension in procreation is what he calls \"moral impediment\": the structural impossibility of acting in the world without harming or manipulating someone at some given moment (not, of course, everyone at every moment). This impediment does not occur because of an intrinsic \"evil\" of human nature, but because of the structural situation in which the human being has always been. In this situation, we are cornered by various kinds of pain, space for action is limited, and different interests often conflict with each other. We do not have to have bad intentions to treat others with disregard; we are compelled to do so in order to survive, pursue our projects and escape from suffering. Cabrera also draws attention to the fact that life is associated with the constant risk of one experiencing strong physical pain, which is common in human life, for example as a result of a serious illness, and maintains that the mere existence of such possibility impedes us morally, as well as that because of it, we can at any time lose, as a result of its occurrence, the possibility of a dignified, moral functioning even to a minimal extent.\n\n=== Kantian imperative ===\n\nJulio Cabrera,<ref>[http://repositorio.unb.br/bitstream/10482/15274/1/LIVRO_PorqueTeAmo.pdf] J. Cabrera, T. Lenharo di Santis, ''Porque...'', op. cit, pp. 52\u201367.</ref> [[David Benatar]]<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better Never to Have Been: The Harm of Coming into Existence'', Oxford: Clarendon Press, 2006, pp. 129\u2013131.</ref> and Karim Akerma<ref>[http://www.tabvlarasa.de/41/Akerma.php] K. Akerma, ''Theodicy shading off into Anthropodicy in Milton, Twain and Kant'', ''Tabula Rasa. Die Kulturzeitung aus Mitteldeutschland'', 2010, number 49.</ref> all argue that procreation is contrary to  [[Immanuel Kant]]'s practical imperative (according to Kant, a man should never be used as a means to an end, but always be an end in himself). They argue that a person can be created for the sake of his parents or other people, but that it is impossible to create someone for his own good; and that therefore, following Kant's recommendation, we should not create new people. Heiko Puls argues that Kant's considerations regarding parental duties and human procreation, in general, imply arguments for an ethically justified antinatalism. Kant, however, according to Puls, rejects this position in his [[teleology]] for [[meta-ethics|meta-ethical]] reasons.<ref>H. Puls, ''Kant\u2019s Justification of Parental Duties'', ''Kantian Review'', 21 (1), 2016, pp. 53\u201375.</ref>\n\n=== Impossibility of consent ===\n\n[[Seana Shiffrin]], Gerald Harrison, Julia Tanner and Asheel Singh argue that procreation is morally problematic because of the impossibility of obtaining consent from the human who will be brought into existence.\n\nShiffrin lists four factors that in her opinion make the justification for having hypothetical consent to procreation a problem:\n\n* (1) great harm is not at stake if the action is not taken;\n* (2) if the action is taken, the harms suffered by the created person can be very severe;\n* (3) a person can not escape the imposed condition without very high cost (suicide is often a physically, emotionally, and morally excruciating option);\n* (4) the hypothetical consent procedure is not based on the values of the person who will bear the imposed condition.<ref>[https://jwcwolf.public.iastate.edu/Papers/Shiffrin%20Wrongful%20life%20procreative%20responsibility%20and%20the%20significance%20of%20harm.pdf] S. Shiffrin, ''Wrongful Life, Procreative Responsibility, and the Significance of Harm'', Cambridge University Press, 1999, p. 133.</ref>\n\nGerald Harrison and Julia Tanner argue that when we want to significantly affect someone by our action and it is not possible to get their consent, then the default should be to not take such action. The exception is, according to them, actions by which we want to prevent greater harm of a person (for example, pushing someone out of the way of a falling piano). However, in their opinion, such actions certainly do not include procreation, because before taking this action a person does not exist.<ref>[https://www.cambridge.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/3AF8BE47794522E31BE351F4D9822344/S1477175610000436a.pdf/better_not_to_have_children.pdf] G. Harrison, J. Tanner, ''Better Not To Have Children'', ''Think'', 2011, volume 10, issue 27, p. 113.</ref><ref>[https://philpapers.org/archive/HARAAA-15] G. Harrison, ''Antinatalism, Asymmetry, and an Ethic of Prima Facie Duties'', ''South African Journal of Philosophy'', volume 31, issue 1, 2012.</ref><ref>[https://commons.pacificu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1629&context=eip] G. Harrison, ''Antinatalism and Moral Particularism'', ''Essays in Philosophy'', ''Is Procreation Immoral?'', volume 20, issue 1, article 5, 2019.</ref>\n\nAsheel Singh emphasizes that one does not have to think that coming into existence is always an overall harm in order to recognize antinatalism as a correct view. In his opinion, it is enough to think that there is no moral right to inflict serious, preventable harms upon others without their consent.<ref>[https://ujcontent.uj.ac.za/vital/access/services/Download/uj:7429/CONTENT1?view=true] A. Singh, ''Assessing anti-natalism: a philosophical examination of the morality of procreation'', University of Johannesburg, 2012, p. 5.</ref>\n\n=== Death as a harm ===\n\nMarc Larock presents a view which he calls \"deprivationalism\".<ref>[https://research-repository.st-andrews.ac.uk/bitstream/handle/10023/717/Marc%20Larock%20MPhil%20thesis.pdf?sequence=6&isAllowed=y] M. Larock, ''Possible preferences and the harm of existence'', University of St. Andrews, 2009.</ref> According to this view:\n* Each person has an interest in acquiring a new satisfied preference.\n* Whenever a person is deprived of a new satisfied preference this violates an interest and thus causes harm.\n\nLarock argues that if a person is deprived of an infinite number of new satisfied [[preference utilitarianism|preferences]], they suffer an infinite number of harms and that such deprivation is death to which procreation leads.\n\n{{quote|All of us are brought into existence, without our consent, and over the course of our lives, we are acquainted with a multitude of goods. Unfortunately, there is a limit to the amount of good each of us will have in our lives. Eventually, each of us will die and we will be permanently cut off from the prospect of any further good. Existence, viewed in this way, seems to be a cruel joke.}}\n\nLarock believes that it is not correct to neutralize his view by stating that death is also an\u00a0infinitely great benefit for us, because it protects us from the infinite number of new frustrated preferences. He proposes a thought experiment in which we have two people, Mary and Tom. The first person, Mary, dies at the age of forty years as a result of complications caused by a [[degenerative disease]]. Mary would live for some more time, if not for the complications, but she would only experience bad things in her life, not good ones. The second person, Tom, dies the same age from the same illness, but in his case, the disease is at such a stage of development that his body would no longer be able to function. According to Larock, it is bad when someone, like in the case of Tom, encounters the impossibility of continuing to derive good things from his life; everybody's life leads to such a point if someone lives long enough and our intuitions do not tell us that this is generally good or even neutral. Therefore, we should reject the view that death is also an infinitely great benefit: because we think that Tom has been unlucky. In the case of Mary, our intuitions tell us that her misfortune is not as great as Tom's misfortune. Her misfortune is reduced by the fact that death saved her from the real prospect of experiencing bad things. We do not have the same intuition in Tom's case. No evil or good future was physically possible for him. Larock thinks that while the impossibility of experiencing future good things seems to us to be a harm, the mere lack of a logical possibility of experiencing future bad things does not seem to be a compensatory benefit to us. If so, there would be nothing strange in recognizing that Tom had not suffered any misfortune. But he is a victim of misfortune, just like Mary. However, Mary's misfortune does not seem to be so great because her death prevents great suffering. Larock is of the opinion that most people will see both cases in this way. This conclusion is supposed to lead to the fact that we recognize that there is an asymmetry between the harms and benefits that death brings.\n\nLarock summarizes his view as follows:\n\n{{quote|The existence of every moral patient in our world rests on a crude moral miscalculation. As I see it, non-procreation is the best means of rectifying this mistake.}}\n\n=== Negative utilitarianism ===\n\n[[Negative utilitarianism]] argues that minimizing suffering has greater moral importance than maximizing happiness.\n\n[[Hermann Vetter]] agrees with the [[The Asymmetry (population ethics)|assumptions]] of [[Jan Narveson]] :<ref>J. Narveson, ''Utilitarianism and New Generations'', ''Mind'', 1967, LXXVI (301), pp. 62\u201367.</ref>\n* (1) There is no moral obligation to produce a child even if we could be sure that it will be very happy throughout its life.\n* (2) There is a moral obligation not to produce a child if it can be foreseen that it will be unhappy.\nHowever, he disagrees with the conclusion that Narveson draws:\n* (3) In general \u2013 if it can be foreseen neither that the child will be unhappy nor that it will bring disutility upon others \u2013 there is no duty to have or not to have a child.\n\nInstead, he presents the following decision-theoretic matrix:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! !! Child will be more or less happy !! Child will be more or less unhappy\n|-\n| Produce the child || No duty fulfilled or violated || Duty violated\n|-\n| Do not produce the child || No duty fulfilled or violated || Duty fulfilled\n|}\n\nBased on this, he concludes that we should not create people:<ref name=autoname4>H. Vetter, ''The production of children as a problem for utilitarian ethics'', ''Inquiry'', 12, 1969, pp. 445\u2013447.</ref><ref>H. Vetter, ''Utilitarianism and New Generations'', ''Mind'', 1971, LXXX (318), pp. 301\u2013302.</ref>\n\n{{quote|It is seen immediately that the act \"do not produce the child\" dominates the act \"produce the child\" because it has equally good consequences as the other act in one case and better consequences in the other. So it is to be preferred to the other act as long as we cannot exclude with certainty the possibility that the child will be more or less unhappy; and we never can. So we have, instead of (3), the far-reaching consequence: (3') In any case, it is morally preferable not to produce a child.}}\n\nKarim Akerma argues that utilitarianism requires the least metaphysical assumptions and is, therefore, the most convincing ethical theory. He believes that negative utilitarianism is the right one because the good things in life do not compensate for the bad things; first and foremost, the best things do not compensate for the worst things such as, for example, the experiences of terrible pain, the agonies of the wounded, sick or dying. In his opinion, we also rarely know what to do to make people happy, but we know what to do so that people do not suffer: it is enough that they are not created. What is important for Akerma in ethics is the striving for the least amount of suffering people (ultimately no one), not striving for the most amount of happy people, which, according to him, takes place at the expense of immeasurable suffering.<ref>K. Akerma, ''Soll eine Menschheit sein? Eine fundamentalethische Frage'', Cuxhaven-Dartford: Traude Junghans, 1995.</ref><ref name=\"autoname2\" />\n\nBruno Contestabile cites the story \"[[The Ones Who Walk Away from Omelas]]\" by [[Ursula K. Le Guin]]. In this story, the existence of the utopian city of Omelas and the good fortune of its inhabitants depend on the suffering of one child tortured in an isolated place and who can not be helped. The majority accepts this state of affairs and stay in the city, but there are those who do not agree with it, who do not want to participate in it and thus they \"walk away from Omelas\". Contestabile draws a parallel here: for Omelas to exist, the child must be tortured, and in the same way, the existence of our world is related to the fact that someone is constantly harmed. According to Contestabile, antinatalists can be seen just as \"the ones who walk away from Omelas\", who do not accept such a world, and who do not approve of its perpetuation. He poses the question: is all happiness able to compensate for the extreme suffering of even one person?<ref>B. Contestabile, ''The Denial of the World from an Impartial View'', ''Contemporary Buddhism: An Interdisciplinary Journal'', volume 17, issue 1, Taylor and Francis, 2016.</ref>\n\n=== David Benatar ===\n\nDavid Benatar argues that there is a crucial asymmetry between the good and the bad things, such as pleasure and pain:\n* (1) the presence of pain is bad;\n* (2) the presence of pleasure is good;\n* (3) the absence of pain is good, even if that good is not enjoyed by anyone;\n* (4) the absence of pleasure is not bad unless there is somebody for whom this absence is a deprivation.<ref>D. Benatar, ''Why it is Better Never to Come Into Existence'', ''American Philosophical Quarterly'', 1997, volume 34, number 3, pp. 345\u2013355.</ref><ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 30\u201340.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Scenario A (X exists) !! Scenario B (X never exists)\n|-\n| (1) Presence of pain (Bad) || (3) Absence of pain (Good)\n|-\n| (2) Presence of pleasure (Good) || (4) Absence of pleasure (Not bad)\n|}\n\nRegarding procreation, the argument follows that coming into existence generates both good and bad experiences, pain and pleasure, whereas not coming into existence entails neither pain nor pleasure. The absence of pain is good, the absence of pleasure is not bad. Therefore, the ethical choice is weighed in favor of non-procreation.\n\nBenatar explains the above asymmetry using four other asymmetries that he considers quite plausible:\n* We have a moral obligation not to create unhappy people and we have no moral obligation to create happy people. The reason why we think there is a moral obligation not to create unhappy people is that the presence of this suffering would be bad (for the sufferers) and the absence of the suffering is good (even though there is nobody to enjoy the absence of suffering). By contrast, the reason we think there is no moral obligation to create happy people is that although their pleasure would be good for them, the absence of pleasure when they do not come into existence will not be bad, because there will be no one who will be deprived of this good.\n* It is strange to mention the interests of a potential child as a reason why we decide to create them, and it is not strange to mention the interests of a potential child as a reason why we decide not to create them. That the child may be happy is not a morally important reason to create them. By contrast, that the child may be unhappy is an important moral reason not to create them. If it were the case that the absence of pleasure is bad even if someone does not exist to experience its absence, then we would have a significant moral reason to create a child and to create as many children as possible. And if it were not the case that the absence of pain is good even if someone does not exist to experience this good, then we would not have a significant moral reason not to create a child.\n* Someday we can regret for the sake of a person whose existence was conditional on our decision, that we created them \u2013 a person can be unhappy and the presence of their pain would be a bad thing. But we will never feel regret for the sake of a person whose existence was conditional on our decision, that we did not create them \u2013 a person will not be deprived of happiness, because he or she will never exist, and the absence of happiness will not be bad, because there will be no one who will be deprived of this good.\n* We feel sadness by the fact that somewhere people come into existence and suffer, and we feel no sadness by the fact that somewhere people did not come into existence in a place where there are happy people. When we know that somewhere people came into existence and suffer, we feel compassion. The fact that on some deserted island or planet people did not come into existence and suffer is good. This is because the absence of pain is good even when there is not someone who is experiencing this good. On the other hand, we do not feel sadness by the fact that on some deserted island or planet people did not come into existence and are not happy. This is because the absence of pleasure is bad only when someone exists to be deprived of this good.\n\nAccording to Benatar, by creating a child, we are responsible not only for this child's suffering, but we may also be co-responsible for the suffering of further offspring of this child.<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 6\u20137.</ref>\n\n{{quote|Assuming that each couple has three children, an original pair's cumulative descendants over ten generations amount to 88,572 people. That constitutes a lot of pointless, avoidable suffering. To be sure, full responsibility for it all does not lie with the original couple because each new generation faces the choice of whether to continue that line of descendants. Nevertheless, they bear some responsibility for the generations that ensue. If one does not desist from having children, one can hardly expect one's descendants to do so.<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 6\u20137 (introduction).</ref>}}\n\nBenatar cites statistics showing where the creation of people leads. It is estimated that:\n* more than fifteen million people are thought to have died from  [[natural disaster]]s in the last 1,000 years,\n* approximately 20,000 people die every day from [[starvation|hunger]],\n* an estimated 840&nbsp;million people suffer from hunger and [[malnutrition]],\n* between 541 and 1912, it is estimated that over 102&nbsp;million people succumbed to [[plague (disease)|plague]],\n* the 1918 [[Spanish flu|influenza epidemic]] killed 50&nbsp;million people,\n* nearly 11&nbsp;million people die every year from [[infectious disease]]s,\n* malignant neoplasms take more than a further 7&nbsp;million lives each year,\n* approximately 3.5&nbsp;million people die every year in accidents,\n* approximately 56.5&nbsp;million people died in 2001, that is more than 107 people per minute,\n* before the twentieth century over 133&nbsp;million people were killed in [[mass murder|mass killings]],\n* in the first 88 years of the twentieth century 170&nbsp;million (and possibly as many as 360&nbsp;million) people were shot, beaten, tortured, knifed, burned, starved, frozen, crushed, or worked to death; buried alive, drowned, hanged, bombed, or killed in any other of the myriad ways governments have inflicted death on unarmed, helpless citizens and foreigners,\n* there were 1.6&nbsp;million conflict-related deaths in the sixteenth century, 6.1&nbsp;million in the seventeenth century, 7&nbsp;million in the eighteenth, 19.4&nbsp;million in the nineteenth, and 109.7&nbsp;million in the twentieth,\n* [[war]]-related injuries led to 310,000 deaths in 2000,\n* about 40&nbsp;million children are [[Child abuse|maltreated]] each year,\n* more than 100&nbsp;million currently living women and girls have been subjected to [[female genital mutilation|genital cutting]],\n* 815,000 people are thought to have committed suicide in 2000<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 88\u201392.</ref> (currently, it is estimated that someone commits suicide every 40 seconds, more than 800,000 people per year).<ref>[https://www.iasp.info/wspd/2016_wspd.php] International Association for Suicide Prevention, ''World Suicide Prevention Day''.</ref>\n\nIn addition to the [[philanthropic]] arguments, which are based on a concern for the humans who will be brought into existence, Benatar also posits that another path to antinatalism is the [[misanthropic]] argument<ref>D. Benatar, D. Wasserman, ''Debating Procreation: Is It Wrong To Reproduce?'', New York: Oxford University Press, 2015, pp. 87\u2013121.</ref> that can be summarized in his opinion as follows:\n\n{{Block quote|Another route to anti-natalism is via what I call a \"misanthropic\" argument. According to this argument, humans are a deeply flawed and a destructive species that is responsible for the suffering and deaths of billions of other humans and non-human animals. If that level of destruction were caused by another species, we would rapidly recommend that new members of that species not be brought into existence.<ref>[http://www.philosophy.uct.ac.za/sites/default/files/image_tool/images/160/We%20Are%20Creatures%20That%20Should%20Not%20Exist%20The%20Theory%20of%20Anti-Natalism%20%28The%20Critique%2015%20July%202015%29.pdf] D. Benatar, ''\"We Are Creatures That Should Not Exist\": The Theory of Anti-Natalism'', ''The Critique'', July 15, 2015.</ref>}}\n\n=== Harm to non-human animals ===\n\nDavid Benatar,<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., p. 109.</ref><ref>D. Benatar, D. Wasserman, ''Debating...'', op. cit., pp. 93\u201399.</ref> Gunter Bleibohm,<ref>G. Bleibohm, ''Fluch der Geburt \u2013 Thesen einer \u00dcberlebensethik'', Landau-Godramstein: Gegensich, 2011.</ref>  Gerald Harrison, Julia Tanner,<ref>G. Harrison, J. Tanner, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 113\u2013121.</ref> and [[Patricia MacCormack]]<ref>P. MacCormack, ''The Ahuman Manifesto: Activism for the End of the Anthropocene'', London-New York-Oxford-New Delhi-Sydney: Bloomsbury Academic, 2020, pp. 47\u201350.</ref> are attentive to the harm caused to other sentient beings by humans. They would say that billions of non-human animals are abused and slaughtered each year by our species for the production of animal products, for experimentation and after the experiments (when they are no longer needed), as a result of the [[destruction of habitats]] or other environmental damage and for sadistic pleasure. They tend to agree with [[animal rights]] thinkers that the harm we do to them is immoral. They consider the human species the most destructive on the planet, arguing that without new humans, there will be no harm caused to other sentient beings by new humans.\n\nSome antinatalists are also [[vegetarians]] or [[vegans]] for moral reasons, and postulate that such views should complement each other as having a common denominator: not causing harm to other sentient beings.<ref>[https://www.pro-iure-animalis.de/index.php/antinatalismus/articles/ist-der-vegetarismus-ein-antinatalismus.html] K. Akerma, ''Ist der Vegetarismus ein Antinatalismus?'', ''Pro iure animalis'', March 24, 2014. [http://akerma.de/Is%20Vegetarianism%20an%20Antinatalism.pdf] English translation.</ref><ref>[https://www.marieclaire.com/culture/a14751412/antinatalism/] V. Pelley, ''This Extreme Sect of Vegans Thinks Your Baby Will Destroy the Planet'', ''Marie Claire'', January 29, 2018.</ref> This attitude was already present in Manichaeism and Catharism.<ref>K. Akerma, ''Antinatalismus...'' op. cit., s. 305.</ref>\n\n=== Environmental impact ===\n\nVolunteers of the [[Voluntary Human Extinction Movement]] argue that human activity is the primary cause of [[environmental degradation]], and therefore refraining from reproduction is \"the humanitarian alternative to human disasters\".<ref>V. Baird, ''The No-nonsense Guide to World Population'', Oxford: New Internationalist, 2011, p. 119.</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rm1QojjwGdo] An NBC interview with Les U. Knight, founder of the Voluntary Human Extinction Movement.</ref><ref>[http://vhemt.org] The official Voluntary Human Extinction Movement website.</ref>\n\n=== Adoption ===\n\nHerman Vetter,<ref name=\"autoname4\" /> Th\u00e9ophile de Giraud,<ref>[http://theophiledegiraud.e-monsite.com/medias/files/manifeste-anti-nataliste.pdf] T. de Giraud, ''L'art de guillotiner les procr\u00e9ateurs: Manifeste anti-nataliste'', Nancy: Le Mort-Qui-Trompe, 2006, p. 51.</ref> Tina Rulli,<ref>T. Rulli, ''The Ethics of Procreation and Adoption'', ''Philosophy Compass'', 11/6, 2016, pp. 305\u2013315.</ref> Karim Akerma<ref>K. Akerma, ''Antinatalismus...'', op. cit., p. 74.</ref> and Julio Cabrera<ref>J.Cabrera, ''Discomfort'', op. cit., p. 181.</ref> argue that presently rather than engaging in the morally problematic act of procreation, one could do good by [[adoption|adopting]] already existing children. De Giraud emphasizes that, across the world, there are millions of existing children who need care.\n\n== Realism ==\n\nSome antinatalists believe that most people do not evaluate reality accurately, which affects the desire to have children.\n\nPeter Wessel Zapffe identifies four repressive mechanisms we use, consciously or not, to restrict our consciousness of life and the world:\n* isolation {{ndash}} an arbitrary dismissal from our consciousness and the consciousness of others about all negative thoughts and feelings associated with the unpleasant facts of our existence. In daily life, this manifests as a tacit agreement to remain silent on certain subjects {{ndash}} especially around children, to prevent instilling in them a fear of the world and what awaits them in life, before they will be able to learn other mechanisms.\n* anchoring {{ndash}} the creation and use of personal values to ensure our attachment to reality, such as parents, home, the street, school, God, the church, the State, morality, fate, the law of life, the people, the future, accumulation of material goods or authority, etc. This can be characterized as creating a defensive structure, \"a fixation of points within, or construction of walls around, the liquid fray of consciousness\", and defending the structure against threats.\n* distraction {{ndash}} shifting focus to new impressions to flee from circumstances and ideas we consider harmful or unpleasant.\n* sublimation {{ndash}} refocusing the tragic parts of life into something creative or valuable, usually through an aesthetic confrontation for the purpose of catharsis. We focus on the imaginary, dramatic, heroic, lyric or comic aspects of life, to allow ourselves and others an escape from their true impact.\n\nAccording to Zapffe, depressive disorders are often \"messages from a deeper, more immediate sense of life, bitter fruits of a geniality of thought\".<ref name=\"autoname3\" /> Some studies seem to confirm this, it is said about the phenomenon of [[depressive realism]], and Colin Feltham writes about antinatalism as one of its possible consequences.<ref>C. Feltham, ''Depressive Realism: Interdisciplinary perspectives'', Abingdon: Routledge, 2016.</ref>\n\nDavid Benatar citing numerous studies lists three phenomena described by psychologists, which, according to him, are responsible for making our self-assessments about the quality of our lives unreliable:\n* [[Optimism bias|Tendency towards optimism]] (or [[Pollyanna principle]]) \u2013 we have a positively distorted picture of our lives in the past, present and future.\n* Adaptation (or accommodation, habituation) \u2013 we adapt to negative situations and adjust our expectations accordingly.\n* Comparison \u2013 for our self-assessments about the quality of our lives, more important than how our lives go is how our they go in comparison with the lives of others. One of the effects of this is that negative aspects of life that affect everyone are not taken into account when assessing our own well-being. We are also more likely to compare ourselves with those who are worse off than those who are better off.\n\nBenatar concludes:\n\n{{quote|The above psychological phenomena are unsurprising from an evolutionary perspective. They militate against suicide and in favour of reproduction. If our lives are quite as bad as I shall still suggest they are, and if people were prone to see this true quality of their lives for what it is, they might be much more inclined to kill themselves, or at least not to produce more such lives. Pessimism, then, tends not to be naturally selected.<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 64\u201369.</ref>}}\n\n[[Thomas Ligotti]] draws attention to the similarity between Zapffe's philosophy and [[terror management theory]]. Terror management theory argues that humans are equipped with unique cognitive abilities beyond what is necessary for survival, which includes symbolic thinking, extensive self-consciousness and perception of themselves as temporal beings aware of the finitude of their existence. The desire to live alongside our awareness of the inevitability of death triggers terror in us. Opposition to this fear is among our primary motivations. To escape it, we build defensive structures around ourselves to ensure our symbolic or literal immortality, to feel like valuable members of a meaningful universe, and to focus on protecting ourselves from immediate external threats.<ref>T. Ligotti, ''The Conspiracy against the Human Race: A Contrivance of Horror'', New York: Hippocampus Press, 2010, pp. 112\u2013113.</ref>\n\n== Abortion ==\n\nAntinatalism can lead to a particular position on the morality of [[abortion]].\n\nAccording to David Benatar, one comes into existence in the morally relevant sense when consciousness arises, when a fetus becomes sentient, and up until that time an abortion is moral, whereas continued pregnancy would be immoral. Benatar refers to [[electroencephalography|EEG]] brain studies and studies on [[prenatal perception|the pain perception of the fetus]], which states that fetal consciousness arises no earlier than between twenty-eight and thirty weeks of pregnancy, before which it is incapable of feeling pain.<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 132\u2013162.</ref> Contrary to that, the latest report from the [[Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists]] showed that the fetus gains consciousness no earlier than week twenty-four of the pregnancy.<ref>[https://www.rcog.org.uk/globalassets/documents/guidelines/rcogfetalawarenesswpr0610.pdf] Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists, ''Fetal Awareness \u2013 Review of Research and Recommendations for Practice'', London: RCOG Press, 2010.</ref> Some assumptions of this report regarding sentience of the fetus after the second trimester were criticized.<ref>[http://fn.bmj.com/content/96/4/F236.long] M. W. Platt, ''Fetal awareness and fetal pain: the Emperor's new clothes'', ''Archives of Disease in Childhood'', 2011, volume 96, issue 4.</ref> In a similar way argues Karim Akerma. He distinguishes between organisms that do not have mental properties and living beings that have mental properties. According to his view, which he calls the mentalistic view, a living being begins to exist when an organism (or another entity) produces a simple form of consciousness for the first time.<ref>K. Akerma, ''Lebensende und Lebensbeginn: Philosophische Implikationen und mentalistische Begr\u00fcndung des Hirn-Todeskriterium'', Lit: Hamburg 2006.</ref><ref>K. Akerma, ''Antinatalismus...'' op. cit., p. 404.</ref>\n\nJulio Cabrera believes that the moral problem of abortion is totally different from the problem of abstention of procreation, because in the case of abortion, there is no longer a non-being, but an already existing being \u2013 the most helpless and defenceless of the parties involved, that someday will have the autonomy to decide, and we cannot decide for them. From the point of view of Cabrera's negative ethics, abortion is immoral for similar reasons as procreation. For Cabrera, the exception in which abortion is morally justified are cases of irreversible illness of the foetus (or some serious \"social illnesses\" like [[Spanish colonization of the Americas|American conquest]] or [[Nazism]]), according to him in such cases we are clearly thinking about the unborn, and not simply of our own interests. In addition, Cabrera believes that under certain circumstances, it is legitimate and comprehensible to commit unethical actions, for example, abortion is a legitimate and comprehensible, when the mother's life is at risk.<ref>[http://repositorio.unb.br/bitstream/10482/15274/1/LIVRO_PorqueTeAmo.pdf] J. Cabrera, T. Lenharo di Santis, op. cit, pp. 68\u201369, 77.</ref><ref>J.Cabrera, ''Discomfort'', op. cit., pp. 208\u2013233.</ref>\n\n== Non-human animals ==\n\nSome antinatalists recognize the procreation of non-human sentient animals as morally bad and sterilization as morally good in their case. Karim Akerma defines antinatalism, that includes non-human sentient animals, as universal antinatalism<ref>K. Akerma, ''Antinatalismus...'' op. cit., pp. 100\u2013101.</ref> and he assumes such a position himself:\n\n{{quote|By sterilising animals, we can free them from being slaves to their instincts and from bringing more and more captive animals into the cycle of being born, contracting parasites, ageing, falling ill and dying; eating and being eaten.<ref>[https://www.pro-iure-animalis.de/dokumente/manifest_antinatalismus.pdf] K. Akerma, ''Manifest zum antinatalismus. Zur Ethik des Antinatalismus. F\u00fcr Nachkommenlosigkeit bei Mensch und Tier'', ''Pro iure animalis'', July 2014. [http://akerma.de/Antinatalist%20Manifesto_Karim%20Akerma.pdf] English translation.</ref>|sign=|source=}}\n\nDavid Benatar emphasizes that his asymmetry applies to all sentient beings, and mentions that humans play a role in deciding how many animals there will be: humans breed other species of animals and are able to sterilize other species of animals.<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 2\u20133 (introduction), 163.</ref>\n\nMagnus Vinding argues that the life of wild animals in their natural environment is generally [[Wild animal suffering|very bad]]. He draws attention to phenomena such as dying before adulthood, starvation, diseases, [[parasites]], [[infanticide]], [[predation]] and being eaten alive. He cites research on what animal life looks like in the wild. One of eight male lion cubs survives into adulthood. Others die as a result of starvation, disease and often fall victims to the teeth and claws of other lions. Attaining adulthood is much rarer for fish. Only one in a hundred male chinook salmon survive into adulthood. Vinding is of the opinion that if human lives and the survival of human children looked like this, current human values would disallow procreation; however, this is not possible when it comes to non-human animals, who are guided by instinct. He takes the view that even if one does not agree that procreation is always morally bad, one should recognize procreation in wildlife as morally bad and something that ought to be prevented (at least in theory, not necessarily in practice). He maintains that non-intervention cannot be defended if we reject [[speciesism]] and that we should reject the unjustifiable [[Appeal to nature|dogma]] stating that what is happening in nature is what should be happening in nature.\n\n{{quote|We cannot allow ourselves to spuriously rationalize away the suffering that takes place in nature, and to forget the victims of the horrors of nature merely because that reality does not fit into our convenient moral theories, theories that ultimately just serve to make us feel consistent and good about ourselves in the face of an incomprehensibly bad reality.<ref>[https://www.smashwords.com/extreader/read/624122/1/the-speciesism-of-leaving-nature-alone-and-the-theoretical-c] M. Vinding, ''The Speciesism of Leaving Nature Alone, and the Theoretical Case for \"Wildlife Anti-Natalism\"'', 2017, ''Apeiron'', 8, pp. 169\u2013183.</ref>}}\n\n==Criticism==\n\nCriticism of antinatalism may come from views that see positive value in bringing humans into existence.<ref>D. Benatar, D. Wasserman, ''Debating...'', op. cit., pp. 133\u2013259.</ref> Results of surveys on subjective [[life satisfaction]], which show a vast surplus of happy people, could suggest that the overall benefit of procreation is greater than the harm and that therefore procreation is morally justified.<ref name=\"autoname4\" /> David Wasserman in his criticism of antinatalism, criticizes, among other things, David Benatar's arguments and the consent argument.<ref>D. Benatar, D. Wasserman, ''Debating...'', op. cit., pp. 148\u2013181.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Audianism]]\n* [[Borborites]]\n* [[Human population planning]]\n* [[Pessimism#Philosophical pessimism|Philosophical pessimism]]\n* [[Priscillianism]]\n* [[Voluntary childlessness]]{{div col end}}\n\n== Notes ==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{wikiquote|Antinatalism}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m7a04MAX2Cg Interview with David Benatar for Cape Talk on Radio 702, about ''Better Never to Have Been'', 2009]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V6DiB3OtFu4 Julio Cabrera's conference ''Birth as a bioethical problem: first steps towards a radical bioethics'' at the University of Bras\u00edlia, 2018]\n* [http://www.ligotti.net/showthread.php?p=93087 ''Antinatalism \u2013 list of books, articles and quotes'']\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-49298720 ''Anti-natalists: The people who want you to stop having babies''],\u00a0''BBC'', August 13, 2019\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/anti-natalists-childfree-population-climate-change ''I wish I'd never been born: the rise of the anti-natalists''], ''The Guardian'', November 14, 2019\n\n[[Category:Antinatalism]]\n[[Category:Bioethics]]\n[[Category:Ethical theories]]\n[[Category:Philosophy of biology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Philosophical position that assigns a negative value to birth}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n'''Antinatalism''', or '''anti-natalism''', is a philosophical position and social movement that assigns a negative [[value (ethics)|value]] to [[birth]]. Antinatalists argue that people should abstain from procreation because it is [[morality|morally]] [[evil|bad]] (some also recognize the procreation of other [[sentience|sentient beings]] as morally bad). In scholarly and in literary writings, various [[ethics|ethical]] foundations have been presented for antinatalism.<ref>K. Akerma, ''Antinatalismus \u2013 Ein Handbuch'', epubli, 2017.</ref> Some of the earliest surviving formulations of the idea that it would be better not to have been born come from ancient Greece.<ref>W. Tatarkiewicz, ''O szcz\u0119\u015bciu'' (''On Happiness''), Warszawa: Pa\u0144stwowe Wydawnictwo Naukowe, 1979, pp. 420\u2013421.</ref> The term antinatalism is in opposition to the term [[natalism]] or pro-natalism, and was used probably for the first time as the name of the position by Belgian philosopher [[Th\u00e9ophile de Giraud]] in his book ''L'art de guillotiner les procr\u00e9ateurs: Manifeste anti-nataliste''.<ref>K. Akerma, ''Antinatalismus...'' op. cit., p. 301.</ref>\n\n== Arguments ==\n\n=== In religion ===\n\nThe teaching of the [[Buddha]], among other [[Four Noble Truths]] and the beginning of [[Khandhaka|Mah\u0101vagga]], is interpreted by [[Hari Singh Gour]] as follows:\n\n{{blockquote|Buddha states his propositions in the pedantic style of his age.  He throws them into a form of sorites; but, as such, it is logically faulty and all he wishes to convey is this:  Oblivious of the suffering to which life is subject, man begets children, and is thus the cause of old age and death.  If he would only realize what suffering he would add to by his act, he would desist from the procreation of children; and so stop the operation of old age and death.<ref>H. Singh Gour, ''The Spirit of Buddhism'', Whitefish, Montana: Kessinger Publishing, 2005, pp. 286\u2013288.</ref>}}\n\nThe [[Marcionites]] believed that the visible world is an evil creation of a crude, cruel, jealous, angry [[demiurge]], [[Yahweh]]. According to this teaching, people should oppose him, abandon his world, not create people, and trust in the good God of mercy, foreign and distant.<ref>H. Jonas, ''The Gnostic Religion: The Message of the Alien God and the Beginnings of Christianity'', Boston: Beacon Press, 1958, pp. 144\u2013145.</ref><ref>P. Karavites, ''Evil, Freedom, and the Road to Perfection in Clement of Alexandria'', Leiden: Brill, 1999, p. 94.</ref><ref>Clement of Alexandria, ''Stromateis, Books 1\u20133 (The Fathers of the Church, volume 85)'', Washington D.C.: CUA Press, 2010, pp. 263\u2013271.</ref>\n\nThe [[Encratites]] observed that birth leads to [[death]]. In order to conquer death, people should desist from procreation:  \"not produce fresh fodder for death\".<ref>P. Brown, ''The Body and Society:  Men, Women, and Sexual Renunciation in Early Christianity'', New York: Columbia University Press, 1988, p. 96.</ref><ref>G. Quispel, ''Gnostica, Judaica, Catholica:  Collected Essays of Gilles Quispel'', Leiden: Brill, 2008, p. 228.</ref><ref>Clement of Alexandria, ''Stromateis'', op. cit., pp. 295\u2013296.</ref>\n\nThe [[Manichaeans]],<ref>H. Jonas, ''The Gnostic...'', op. cit., pp. 228, 231.</ref><ref>I. Gardner and S.N.C. Lieu, ''Manichaean Texts from the Roman Empire'', New York: Cambridge University Press, 2004, pp. 7, 22.</ref><ref>S.G. Kochuthara, ''The Concept of Sexual Pleasure in the Catholic Moral Tradition'', Rome: Gregorian Biblical BookShop, 2007, p. 165.</ref> the [[Bogomils]]<ref>D. Obolensky, ''The Bogomils: A Study in Balkan Neo-Manichaeism'', New York: Cambridge University Press, 2004, p. 114.</ref><ref>F. Curta, ''Southeastern Europe in the Middle Ages, 500\u20131250'', New York: Cambridge University Press, 2006, p. 236.</ref><ref>J. Lacarri\u00e8re, ''The Gnostics'', London: Owen, 1977, p. 116.</ref> and the [[Cathars]]<ref>M.J. Fromer, ''Ethical issues in Sexuality and Reproduction'', St. Louis: Mosby, 1983, p. 110.</ref><ref>S. Runciman, ''The Medieval Manichee:  A Study of the Christian Dualist Heresy'', New York: Cambridge University Press, 1947, pp. 151\u2013152.</ref><ref>D. Elliott, ''Spiritual Marriage: Sexual Abstinence in Medieval Wedlock'', Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1995, pp. 133\u2013134.</ref> believed that procreation sentences the soul to imprisonment in evil matter. They saw procreation as an instrument of an [[Dualistic cosmology#In Christianity|evil god]], demiurge, or of [[Satan]] that imprisons the divine element in matter and thus causes the divine element to suffer.\n\n=== Theodicy and anthropodicy ===\n\n[[Julio Cabrera (philosopher)|Julio Cabrera]] considers the issue of being a creator in relation to [[theodicy]] and argues that just as it is impossible to defend the idea of a good [[God]] as creator, it is also impossible to defend the idea of a good man as creator. In parenthood, the human parent imitates the divine parent, in the sense that education could be understood as a form of pursuit of \"salvation\", the \"right path\" for a child. However, a human being could decide that it is better not to suffer at all than to suffer and be offered the later possibility of salvation from suffering. In Cabrera's opinion, evil is associated not with the [[nothing|lack of being]], but with the suffering and dying of those that are alive. So, on the contrary, evil is only and obviously associated with [[being]].<ref name=autoname1>J. Cabrera, ''Projeto de \u00c9tica Negativa'', S\u00e3o Paulo: Edic\u00f5es Mandacaru, 1989 (second edition: ''A \u00c9tica e Suas Nega\u00e7\u00f5es, N\u00e3o nascer, suic\u00eddio e pequenos assassinatos'', Rio De Janeiro: Rocco, 2011). [https://misantropiaemelancolia.wordpress.com/2017/10/24/project-of-negative-ethics/] English translation of the first chapter.</ref>\n\nKarim Akerma, due to the moral problem of man as creator, introduces anthropodicy, a twin concept for theodicy. He is of the opinion that the less faith in the Almighty Creator-God there is, the more urgent the question of anthropodicy becomes. Akerma thinks that for those who want to lead ethical lives, the causation of suffering requires a justification. Man can no longer shed responsibility for the suffering that occurs by appealing to an imaginary entity that sets moral principles. For Akerma, antinatalism is a consequence of the collapse of theodicy endeavours and the failure of attempts to establish an anthropodizee. According to him, there is no metaphysics nor moral theory that can justify the production of new people, and therefore anthropodicy is indefensible as well as theodicy.<ref name=autoname2>K. Akerma, ''Verebben der Menschheit?: Neganthropie und Anthropodizee'', Verlag Karl Alber, Freiburg im Breisgau: Verlag Karl Alber, 2000.</ref>\n\n=== Peter Wessel Zapffe ===\n\n[[Peter Wessel Zapffe]] viewed humans as a biological paradox. According to him, [[consciousness]] has become over-evolved in humans, thereby making us incapable of functioning normally like other animals: cognition gives us more than we can carry. Our frailness and insignificance in the cosmos are visible to us. We want to live, and yet because of how we have evolved, we are the only species whose members are conscious that they are destined to die. We are able to analyze the past and the future, both our situation and that of others, as well as to imagine the suffering of billions of people (as well as of other living beings) and feel [[compassion]] for their suffering. We yearn for justice and meaning in a world that lacks both. This ensures that the lives of conscious individuals are tragic. We have desires: spiritual needs which reality is unable to satisfy, and our species still exists only because we limit our awareness of what that reality actually entails. Human existence amounts to a tangled network of defense mechanisms, which can be observed both individually and socially, in our everyday behavior patterns. According to Zapffe, humanity should cease this self-deception, and the natural consequence would be its [[extinction]] by abstaining from procreation.<ref name=autoname3>P.W. Zapffe, ''The Last Messiah'', ''Philosophy Now'', 2004, number 45, pp. 35\u201339.</ref><ref>P. W. Zapffe, ''Om det tragiske'', Oslo: Pax Forlag, 1996.</ref><ref>P. W. Zapffe, H. T\u00f8nnessen, ''Jeg velger sannheten: En dialog mellom Peter Wessel Zapffe og Herman T\u00f8nnessen'', Oslo: Universitets forlaget, 1983.</ref>\n\n=== Negative ethics ===\n\nJulio Cabrera proposes a concept of \"negative ethics\" in opposition to \"affirmative\" ethics, meaning ethics that affirm [[dasein|being]].<ref name=\"autoname1\" /><ref>[http://repositorio.unb.br/bitstream/10482/17430/3/Livro_CritiqueAffirmativeMorality.pdf] J. Cabrera, ''A critique of affirmative morality (A reflection on death, birth and the value of life)'', Bras\u00edlia: Julio Cabrera Editions, 2014 (English edition). J. Cabrera, ''Cr\u00edtica de la moral afirmativa: Una reflexi\u00f3n sobre nacimiento, muerte y valor de la vida'', Barcelona: Gedisa, 1996 (original Spanish edition, second edition in 2014).</ref><ref>J. Cabrera (editor), ''\u00c9tica Negativa: problemas e discuss\u00f5es'', Goi\u00e2nia: UFG, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://repositorio.unb.br/bitstream/10482/15274/1/LIVRO_PorqueTeAmo.pdf] J. Cabrera, T. Lenharo di Santis, ''Porque te amo, N\u00e3o nascer\u00e1s!: Nascituri te salutant'', Bras\u00edlia: LGE, 2009.\n[https://misantropiaemelancolia.wordpress.com/2017/09/28/first-chapter-of-nascituri-te-salutant/] English translation.</ref><ref>J. Cabrera, ''Discomfort and Moral Impediment: The Human Situation, Radical Bioethics and Procreation'', Newcastle upon Tyne: Cambridge Scholars Publishing, 2019. [https://www.cambridgescholars.com/discomfort-and-moral-impediment] A thirty-page extract on the publisher's website. J. Cabrera, ''Mal-estar e moralidade: situa\u00e7\u00e3o humana, \u00e9tica e procria\u00e7\u00e3o respons\u00e1vel'', Bras\u00edlia: UnB, 2018 (original Portuguese edition).</ref> He describes procreation as manipulation and harm, a unilateral and non-consensual sending of a human being into a painful, dangerous and morally impeding situation.\n\nCabrera regards procreation as an [[ontology|ontological]] issue of total manipulation: one's very being is manufactured and used; in contrast to intra-worldly cases where someone is placed in a harmful situation. In the case of procreation no chance of defense against that act is even available. According to Cabrera: manipulation in procreation is visible primarily in the unilateral and non-consensual nature of the act, which makes procreation per se inevitably asymmetrical; be it a product of forethought, or a product of neglect. It is always connected with the interests (or disinterests) of other humans, not the created human. In addition, Cabrera points out that in his view the manipulation of procreation is not limited to the act of creation itself, but it is continued in the process of raising the child, during which parents gain great power over the child's life, who is shaped according to their preferences and for their satisfaction. He emphasizes that although it is not possible to avoid manipulation in procreation, it is perfectly possible to avoid procreation itself and that then no moral rule is violated.\n\nCabrera believes that the situation in which one is placed through procreation, human life, is structurally negative in that its constitutive features are inherently adverse. The most prominent of them are, according to Cabrera, the following:\n* (a) The being acquired by a human at birth is decreasing (or \"decaying\"), in the sense of a being that begins to end since its very emergence, following a single and irreversible direction of deterioration and decline, of which complete consummation can occur at any moment between some minutes and around one hundred years.\n* (b) From the moment they come into being, humans are affected by three kinds of frictions: physical pain (in the form of illnesses, accidents and natural catastrophes to which they are always exposed); discouragement (in the form of \"lacking the will\", or the \"mood\" or the \"spirit\", to continue to act, from mild taedium vitae to serious forms of depression), and finally, exposure to the aggressions of other humans (from gossip and slander to various forms of discrimination, persecution and injustice), aggressions that we too can inflict on others, also submitted, like us, to the three kinds of friction.\n* (c) To defend themselves against (a) and (b), human beings are equipped with mechanisms of creation of positive values (ethical, [[aesthetic]], [[religious]], [[entertaining]], [[recreational]], as well as values contained in human realizations of all kinds), which humans must keep constantly active. All positive values that appear within human life are reactive and palliative; they are introduced by the permanent, anxious and uncertain struggle against the decaying life and its three kinds of friction.\n\nCabrera calls the set of these characteristics A\u2013C the \"terminality of being\". He is of the opinion that a huge number of humans around the world cannot withstand this steep struggle against the terminal structure of their being, which leads to destructive consequences for them and others: [[suicide]]s, major or minor [[mental disorder|mental illnesses]], or [[aggression|aggressive behavior]]. He accepts that life may be \u2013 thanks to human's own merits and efforts \u2013 bearable and even very pleasant (though not for all, due to the phenomenon of moral impediment), but also considers it problematic to bring someone into existence so that they may attempt to make their life pleasant by struggling against the difficult and oppressive situation we place them in by procreating. It seems more reasonable, according to Cabrera, simply not to put them in that situation, since the results of their struggle are always uncertain.\n\nCabrera believes that in ethics, including affirmative ethics, there is one overarching concept which he calls the \"Minimal Ethical Articulation\", \"MEA\" (previously translated into English as \"Fundamental Ethical Articulation\" and \"FEA\"): the consideration of other people's interests, not manipulating them and not harming them. Procreation for him is an obvious violation of MEA \u2013 someone is manipulated and placed in a harmful situation as a result of that action. In his view, values included in the MEA are widely accepted by affirmative ethics, they are even their basics, and if approached [[hypocrisy|radically]], they should lead to the refusal of procreation.\n\nFor Cabrera, the worst thing in human life and by extension in procreation is what he calls \"moral impediment\": the structural impossibility of acting morally towards everyone in all circumstances. This impediment does not occur because of an intrinsic \"evil\" of human nature, but because of the structural situation in which the human being has always been. In this situation, we are cornered by various kinds of pain, space for action is limited, and different interests often conflict with each other. We do not have to have bad intentions to treat others with disregard; we are compelled to do so in order to survive, pursue our projects and escape from suffering. Cabrera also draws attention to the fact that life is associated with the constant risk of one experiencing strong physical pain, which is common in human life, for example as a result of a serious illness, and maintains that the mere existence of such possibility impedes us morally, as well as that because of it, we can at any time lose, as a result of its occurrence, the possibility of a dignified, moral functioning even to a minimal extent.\n\n=== Kantian imperative ===\n\nJulio Cabrera,<ref>[http://repositorio.unb.br/bitstream/10482/15274/1/LIVRO_PorqueTeAmo.pdf] J. Cabrera, T. Lenharo di Santis, ''Porque...'', op. cit, pp. 52\u201367.</ref> [[David Benatar]]<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better Never to Have Been: The Harm of Coming into Existence'', Oxford: Clarendon Press, 2006, pp. 129\u2013131.</ref> and Karim Akerma<ref>[http://www.tabvlarasa.de/41/Akerma.php] K. Akerma, ''Theodicy shading off into Anthropodicy in Milton, Twain and Kant'', ''Tabula Rasa. Die Kulturzeitung aus Mitteldeutschland'', 2010, number 49.</ref> all argue that procreation is contrary to  [[Immanuel Kant]]'s practical imperative (according to Kant, a man should never be used as a means to an end, but always be an end in himself). They argue that a person can be created for the sake of his parents or other people, but that it is impossible to create someone for his own good; and that therefore, following Kant's recommendation, we should not create new people. Heiko Puls argues that Kant's considerations regarding parental duties and human procreation, in general, imply arguments for an ethically justified antinatalism. Kant, however, according to Puls, rejects this position in his [[teleology]] for [[meta-ethics|meta-ethical]] reasons.<ref>H. Puls, ''Kant\u2019s Justification of Parental Duties'', ''Kantian Review'', 21 (1), 2016, pp. 53\u201375.</ref>\n\n=== Impossibility of consent ===\n\n[[Seana Shiffrin]], Gerald Harrison, Julia Tanner and Asheel Singh argue that procreation is morally problematic because of the impossibility of obtaining consent from the human who will be brought into existence.\n\nShiffrin lists four factors that in her opinion make the justification for having hypothetical consent to procreation a problem:\n\n* (1) great harm is not at stake if the action is not taken;\n* (2) if the action is taken, the harms suffered by the created person can be very severe;\n* (3) a person can not escape the imposed condition without very high cost (suicide is often a physically, emotionally, and morally excruciating option);\n* (4) the hypothetical consent procedure is not based on the values of the person who will bear the imposed condition.<ref>[https://jwcwolf.public.iastate.edu/Papers/Shiffrin%20Wrongful%20life%20procreative%20responsibility%20and%20the%20significance%20of%20harm.pdf] S. Shiffrin, ''Wrongful Life, Procreative Responsibility, and the Significance of Harm'', Cambridge University Press, 1999, p. 133.</ref>\n\nGerald Harrison and Julia Tanner argue that when we want to significantly affect someone by our action and it is not possible to get their consent, then the default should be to not take such action. The exception is, according to them, actions by which we want to prevent greater harm of a person (for example, pushing someone out of the way of a falling piano). However, in their opinion, such actions certainly do not include procreation, because before taking this action a person does not exist.<ref>[https://www.cambridge.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/3AF8BE47794522E31BE351F4D9822344/S1477175610000436a.pdf/better_not_to_have_children.pdf] G. Harrison, J. Tanner, ''Better Not To Have Children'', ''Think'', 2011, volume 10, issue 27, p. 113.</ref><ref>[https://philpapers.org/archive/HARAAA-15] G. Harrison, ''Antinatalism, Asymmetry, and an Ethic of Prima Facie Duties'', ''South African Journal of Philosophy'', volume 31, issue 1, 2012.</ref><ref>[https://commons.pacificu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1629&context=eip] G. Harrison, ''Antinatalism and Moral Particularism'', ''Essays in Philosophy'', ''Is Procreation Immoral?'', volume 20, issue 1, article 5, 2019.</ref>\n\nAsheel Singh emphasizes that one does not have to think that coming into existence is always an overall harm in order to recognize antinatalism as a correct view. In his opinion, it is enough to think that there is no moral right to inflict serious, preventable harms upon others without their consent.<ref>[https://ujcontent.uj.ac.za/vital/access/services/Download/uj:7429/CONTENT1?view=true] A. Singh, ''Assessing anti-natalism: a philosophical examination of the morality of procreation'', University of Johannesburg, 2012, p. 5.</ref>\n\n=== Death as a harm ===\n\nMarc Larock presents a view which he calls \"deprivationalism\".<ref>[https://research-repository.st-andrews.ac.uk/bitstream/handle/10023/717/Marc%20Larock%20MPhil%20thesis.pdf?sequence=6&isAllowed=y] M. Larock, ''Possible preferences and the harm of existence'', University of St. Andrews, 2009.</ref> According to this view:\n* Each person has an interest in acquiring a new satisfied preference.\n* Whenever a person is deprived of a new satisfied preference this violates an interest and thus causes harm.\n\nLarock argues that if a person is deprived of an infinite number of new satisfied [[preference utilitarianism|preferences]], they suffer an infinite number of harms and that such deprivation is death to which procreation leads.\n\n{{quote|All of us are brought into existence, without our consent, and over the course of our lives, we are acquainted with a multitude of goods. Unfortunately, there is a limit to the amount of good each of us will have in our lives. Eventually, each of us will die and we will be permanently cut off from the prospect of any further good. Existence, viewed in this way, seems to be a cruel joke.}}\n\nLarock believes that it is not correct to neutralize his view by stating that death is also an\u00a0infinitely great benefit for us, because it protects us from the infinite number of new frustrated preferences. He proposes a thought experiment in which we have two people, Mary and Tom. The first person, Mary, dies at the age of forty years as a result of complications caused by a [[degenerative disease]]. Mary would live for some more time, if not for the complications, but she would only experience bad things in her life, not good ones. The second person, Tom, dies the same age from the same illness, but in his case, the disease is at such a stage of development that his body would no longer be able to function. According to Larock, it is bad when someone, like in the case of Tom, encounters the impossibility of continuing to derive good things from his life; everybody's life leads to such a point if someone lives long enough and our intuitions do not tell us that this is generally good or even neutral. Therefore, we should reject the view that death is also an infinitely great benefit: because we think that Tom has been unlucky. In the case of Mary, our intuitions tell us that her misfortune is not as great as Tom's misfortune. Her misfortune is reduced by the fact that death saved her from the real prospect of experiencing bad things. We do not have the same intuition in Tom's case. No evil or good future was physically possible for him. Larock thinks that while the impossibility of experiencing future good things seems to us to be a harm, the mere lack of a logical possibility of experiencing future bad things does not seem to be a compensatory benefit to us. If so, there would be nothing strange in recognizing that Tom had not suffered any misfortune. But he is a victim of misfortune, just like Mary. However, Mary's misfortune does not seem to be so great because her death prevents great suffering. Larock is of the opinion that most people will see both cases in this way. This conclusion is supposed to lead to the fact that we recognize that there is an asymmetry between the harms and benefits that death brings.\n\nLarock summarizes his view as follows:\n\n{{quote|The existence of every moral patient in our world rests on a crude moral miscalculation. As I see it, non-procreation is the best means of rectifying this mistake.}}\n\n=== Negative utilitarianism ===\n\n[[Negative utilitarianism]] argues that minimizing suffering has greater moral importance than maximizing happiness.\n\n[[Hermann Vetter]] agrees with the [[The Asymmetry (population ethics)|assumptions]] of [[Jan Narveson]] :<ref>J. Narveson, ''Utilitarianism and New Generations'', ''Mind'', 1967, LXXVI (301), pp. 62\u201367.</ref>\n* (1) There is no moral obligation to produce a child even if we could be sure that it will be very happy throughout its life.\n* (2) There is a moral obligation not to produce a child if it can be foreseen that it will be unhappy.\nHowever, he disagrees with the conclusion that Narveson draws:\n* (3) In general \u2013 if it can be foreseen neither that the child will be unhappy nor that it will bring disutility upon others \u2013 there is no duty to have or not to have a child.\n\nInstead, he presents the following decision-theoretic matrix:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! !! Child will be more or less happy !! Child will be more or less unhappy\n|-\n| Produce the child || No duty fulfilled or violated || Duty violated\n|-\n| Do not produce the child || No duty fulfilled or violated || Duty fulfilled\n|}\n\nBased on this, he concludes that we should not create people:<ref name=autoname4>H. Vetter, ''The production of children as a problem for utilitarian ethics'', ''Inquiry'', 12, 1969, pp. 445\u2013447.</ref><ref>H. Vetter, ''Utilitarianism and New Generations'', ''Mind'', 1971, LXXX (318), pp. 301\u2013302.</ref>\n\n{{quote|It is seen immediately that the act \"do not produce the child\" dominates the act \"produce the child\" because it has equally good consequences as the other act in one case and better consequences in the other. So it is to be preferred to the other act as long as we cannot exclude with certainty the possibility that the child will be more or less unhappy; and we never can. So we have, instead of (3), the far-reaching consequence: (3') In any case, it is morally preferable not to produce a child.}}\n\nKarim Akerma argues that utilitarianism requires the least metaphysical assumptions and is, therefore, the most convincing ethical theory. He believes that negative utilitarianism is the right one because the good things in life do not compensate for the bad things; first and foremost, the best things do not compensate for the worst things such as, for example, the experiences of terrible pain, the agonies of the wounded, sick or dying. In his opinion, we also rarely know what to do to make people happy, but we know what to do so that people do not suffer: it is enough that they are not created. What is important for Akerma in ethics is the striving for the least amount of suffering people (ultimately no one), not striving for the most amount of happy people, which, according to him, takes place at the expense of immeasurable suffering.<ref>K. Akerma, ''Soll eine Menschheit sein? Eine fundamentalethische Frage'', Cuxhaven-Dartford: Traude Junghans, 1995.</ref><ref name=\"autoname2\" />\n\nBruno Contestabile cites the story \"[[The Ones Who Walk Away from Omelas]]\" by [[Ursula K. Le Guin]]. In this story, the existence of the utopian city of Omelas and the good fortune of its inhabitants depend on the suffering of one child tortured in an isolated place and who can not be helped. The majority accepts this state of affairs and stay in the city, but there are those who do not agree with it, who do not want to participate in it and thus they \"walk away from Omelas\". Contestabile draws a parallel here: for Omelas to exist, the child must be tortured, and in the same way, the existence of our world is related to the fact that someone is constantly harmed. According to Contestabile, antinatalists can be seen just as \"the ones who walk away from Omelas\", who do not accept such a world, and who do not approve of its perpetuation. He poses the question: is all happiness able to compensate for the extreme suffering of even one person?<ref>B. Contestabile, ''The Denial of the World from an Impartial View'', ''Contemporary Buddhism: An Interdisciplinary Journal'', volume 17, issue 1, Taylor and Francis, 2016.</ref>\n\n=== David Benatar ===\n\nDavid Benatar argues that there is a crucial asymmetry between the good and the bad things, such as pleasure and pain:\n* (1) the presence of pain is bad;\n* (2) the presence of pleasure is good;\n* (3) the absence of pain is good, even if that good is not enjoyed by anyone;\n* (4) the absence of pleasure is not bad unless there is somebody for whom this absence is a deprivation.<ref>D. Benatar, ''Why it is Better Never to Come Into Existence'', ''American Philosophical Quarterly'', 1997, volume 34, number 3, pp. 345\u2013355.</ref><ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 30\u201340.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Scenario A (X exists) !! Scenario B (X never exists)\n|-\n| (1) Presence of pain (Bad) || (3) Absence of pain (Good)\n|-\n| (2) Presence of pleasure (Good) || (4) Absence of pleasure (Not bad)\n|}\n\nRegarding procreation, the argument follows that coming into existence generates both good and bad experiences, pain and pleasure, whereas not coming into existence entails neither pain nor pleasure. The absence of pain is good, the absence of pleasure is not bad. Therefore, the ethical choice is weighed in favor of non-procreation.\n\nBenatar explains the above asymmetry using four other asymmetries that he considers quite plausible:\n* We have a moral obligation not to create unhappy people and we have no moral obligation to create happy people. The reason why we think there is a moral obligation not to create unhappy people is that the presence of this suffering would be bad (for the sufferers) and the absence of the suffering is good (even though there is nobody to enjoy the absence of suffering). By contrast, the reason we think there is no moral obligation to create happy people is that although their pleasure would be good for them, the absence of pleasure when they do not come into existence will not be bad, because there will be no one who will be deprived of this good.\n* It is strange to mention the interests of a potential child as a reason why we decide to create them, and it is not strange to mention the interests of a potential child as a reason why we decide not to create them. That the child may be happy is not a morally important reason to create them. By contrast, that the child may be unhappy is an important moral reason not to create them. If it were the case that the absence of pleasure is bad even if someone does not exist to experience its absence, then we would have a significant moral reason to create a child and to create as many children as possible. And if it were not the case that the absence of pain is good even if someone does not exist to experience this good, then we would not have a significant moral reason not to create a child.\n* Someday we can regret for the sake of a person whose existence was conditional on our decision, that we created them \u2013 a person can be unhappy and the presence of their pain would be a bad thing. But we will never feel regret for the sake of a person whose existence was conditional on our decision, that we did not create them \u2013 a person will not be deprived of happiness, because he or she will never exist, and the absence of happiness will not be bad, because there will be no one who will be deprived of this good.\n* We feel sadness by the fact that somewhere people come into existence and suffer, and we feel no sadness by the fact that somewhere people did not come into existence in a place where there are happy people. When we know that somewhere people came into existence and suffer, we feel compassion. The fact that on some deserted island or planet people did not come into existence and suffer is good. This is because the absence of pain is good even when there is not someone who is experiencing this good. On the other hand, we do not feel sadness by the fact that on some deserted island or planet people did not come into existence and are not happy. This is because the absence of pleasure is bad only when someone exists to be deprived of this good.\n\nAccording to Benatar, by creating a child, we are responsible not only for this child's suffering, but we may also be co-responsible for the suffering of further offspring of this child.<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 6\u20137.</ref>\n\n{{quote|Assuming that each couple has three children, an original pair's cumulative descendants over ten generations amount to 88,572 people. That constitutes a lot of pointless, avoidable suffering. To be sure, full responsibility for it all does not lie with the original couple because each new generation faces the choice of whether to continue that line of descendants. Nevertheless, they bear some responsibility for the generations that ensue. If one does not desist from having children, one can hardly expect one's descendants to do so.<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 6\u20137 (introduction).</ref>}}\n\nBenatar cites statistics showing where the creation of people leads. It is estimated that:\n* more than fifteen million people are thought to have died from  [[natural disaster]]s in the last 1,000 years,\n* approximately 20,000 people die every day from [[starvation|hunger]],\n* an estimated 840&nbsp;million people suffer from hunger and [[malnutrition]],\n* between 541 and 1912, it is estimated that over 102&nbsp;million people succumbed to [[plague (disease)|plague]],\n* the 1918 [[Spanish flu|influenza epidemic]] killed 50&nbsp;million people,\n* nearly 11&nbsp;million people die every year from [[infectious disease]]s,\n* malignant neoplasms take more than a further 7&nbsp;million lives each year,\n* approximately 3.5&nbsp;million people die every year in accidents,\n* approximately 56.5&nbsp;million people died in 2001, that is more than 107 people per minute,\n* before the twentieth century over 133&nbsp;million people were killed in [[mass murder|mass killings]],\n* in the first 88 years of the twentieth century 170&nbsp;million (and possibly as many as 360&nbsp;million) people were shot, beaten, tortured, knifed, burned, starved, frozen, crushed, or worked to death; buried alive, drowned, hanged, bombed, or killed in any other of the myriad ways governments have inflicted death on unarmed, helpless citizens and foreigners,\n* there were 1.6&nbsp;million conflict-related deaths in the sixteenth century, 6.1&nbsp;million in the seventeenth century, 7&nbsp;million in the eighteenth, 19.4&nbsp;million in the nineteenth, and 109.7&nbsp;million in the twentieth,\n* [[war]]-related injuries led to 310,000 deaths in 2000,\n* about 40&nbsp;million children are [[Child abuse|maltreated]] each year,\n* more than 100&nbsp;million currently living women and girls have been subjected to [[female genital mutilation|genital cutting]],\n* 815,000 people are thought to have committed suicide in 2000<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 88\u201392.</ref> (currently, it is estimated that someone commits suicide every 40 seconds, more than 800,000 people per year).<ref>[https://www.iasp.info/wspd/2016_wspd.php] International Association for Suicide Prevention, ''World Suicide Prevention Day''.</ref>\n\nIn addition to the [[philanthropic]] arguments, which are based on a concern for the humans who will be brought into existence, Benatar also posits that another path to antinatalism is the [[misanthropic]] argument<ref>D. Benatar, D. Wasserman, ''Debating Procreation: Is It Wrong To Reproduce?'', New York: Oxford University Press, 2015, pp. 87\u2013121.</ref> that can be summarized in his opinion as follows:\n\n{{Block quote|Another route to anti-natalism is via what I call a \"misanthropic\" argument. According to this argument, humans are a deeply flawed and a destructive species that is responsible for the suffering and deaths of billions of other humans and non-human animals. If that level of destruction were caused by another species, we would rapidly recommend that new members of that species not be brought into existence.<ref>[http://www.philosophy.uct.ac.za/sites/default/files/image_tool/images/160/We%20Are%20Creatures%20That%20Should%20Not%20Exist%20The%20Theory%20of%20Anti-Natalism%20%28The%20Critique%2015%20July%202015%29.pdf] D. Benatar, ''\"We Are Creatures That Should Not Exist\": The Theory of Anti-Natalism'', ''The Critique'', July 15, 2015.</ref>}}\n\n=== Harm to non-human animals ===\n\nDavid Benatar,<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., p. 109.</ref><ref>D. Benatar, D. Wasserman, ''Debating...'', op. cit., pp. 93\u201399.</ref> Gunter Bleibohm,<ref>G. Bleibohm, ''Fluch der Geburt \u2013 Thesen einer \u00dcberlebensethik'', Landau-Godramstein: Gegensich, 2011.</ref>  Gerald Harrison, Julia Tanner,<ref>G. Harrison, J. Tanner, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 113\u2013121.</ref> and [[Patricia MacCormack]]<ref>P. MacCormack, ''The Ahuman Manifesto: Activism for the End of the Anthropocene'', London-New York-Oxford-New Delhi-Sydney: Bloomsbury Academic, 2020, pp. 47\u201350.</ref> are attentive to the harm caused to other sentient beings by humans. They would say that billions of non-human animals are abused and slaughtered each year by our species for the production of animal products, for experimentation and after the experiments (when they are no longer needed), as a result of the [[destruction of habitats]] or other environmental damage and for sadistic pleasure. They tend to agree with [[animal rights]] thinkers that the harm we do to them is immoral. They consider the human species the most destructive on the planet, arguing that without new humans, there will be no harm caused to other sentient beings by new humans.\n\nSome antinatalists are also [[vegetarians]] or [[vegans]] for moral reasons, and postulate that such views should complement each other as having a common denominator: not causing harm to other sentient beings.<ref>[https://www.pro-iure-animalis.de/index.php/antinatalismus/articles/ist-der-vegetarismus-ein-antinatalismus.html] K. Akerma, ''Ist der Vegetarismus ein Antinatalismus?'', ''Pro iure animalis'', March 24, 2014. [http://akerma.de/Is%20Vegetarianism%20an%20Antinatalism.pdf] English translation.</ref><ref>[https://www.marieclaire.com/culture/a14751412/antinatalism/] V. Pelley, ''This Extreme Sect of Vegans Thinks Your Baby Will Destroy the Planet'', ''Marie Claire'', January 29, 2018.</ref> This attitude was already present in Manichaeism and Catharism.<ref>K. Akerma, ''Antinatalismus...'' op. cit., s. 305.</ref>\n\n=== Environmental impact ===\n\nVolunteers of the [[Voluntary Human Extinction Movement]] argue that human activity is the primary cause of [[environmental degradation]], and therefore refraining from reproduction is \"the humanitarian alternative to human disasters\".<ref>V. Baird, ''The No-nonsense Guide to World Population'', Oxford: New Internationalist, 2011, p. 119.</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rm1QojjwGdo] An NBC interview with Les U. Knight, founder of the Voluntary Human Extinction Movement.</ref><ref>[http://vhemt.org] The official Voluntary Human Extinction Movement website.</ref>\n\n=== Adoption ===\n\nHerman Vetter,<ref name=\"autoname4\" /> Th\u00e9ophile de Giraud,<ref>[http://theophiledegiraud.e-monsite.com/medias/files/manifeste-anti-nataliste.pdf] T. de Giraud, ''L'art de guillotiner les procr\u00e9ateurs: Manifeste anti-nataliste'', Nancy: Le Mort-Qui-Trompe, 2006, p. 51.</ref> Tina Rulli,<ref>T. Rulli, ''The Ethics of Procreation and Adoption'', ''Philosophy Compass'', 11/6, 2016, pp. 305\u2013315.</ref> Karim Akerma<ref>K. Akerma, ''Antinatalismus...'', op. cit., p. 74.</ref> and Julio Cabrera<ref>J.Cabrera, ''Discomfort'', op. cit., p. 181.</ref> argue that presently rather than engaging in the morally problematic act of procreation, one could do good by [[adoption|adopting]] already existing children. De Giraud emphasizes that, across the world, there are millions of existing children who need care.\n\n== Realism ==\n\nSome antinatalists believe that most people do not evaluate reality accurately, which affects the desire to have children.\n\nPeter Wessel Zapffe identifies four repressive mechanisms we use, consciously or not, to restrict our consciousness of life and the world:\n* isolation {{ndash}} an arbitrary dismissal from our consciousness and the consciousness of others about all negative thoughts and feelings associated with the unpleasant facts of our existence. In daily life, this manifests as a tacit agreement to remain silent on certain subjects {{ndash}} especially around children, to prevent instilling in them a fear of the world and what awaits them in life, before they will be able to learn other mechanisms.\n* anchoring {{ndash}} the creation and use of personal values to ensure our attachment to reality, such as parents, home, the street, school, God, the church, the State, morality, fate, the law of life, the people, the future, accumulation of material goods or authority, etc. This can be characterized as creating a defensive structure, \"a fixation of points within, or construction of walls around, the liquid fray of consciousness\", and defending the structure against threats.\n* distraction {{ndash}} shifting focus to new impressions to flee from circumstances and ideas we consider harmful or unpleasant.\n* sublimation {{ndash}} refocusing the tragic parts of life into something creative or valuable, usually through an aesthetic confrontation for the purpose of catharsis. We focus on the imaginary, dramatic, heroic, lyric or comic aspects of life, to allow ourselves and others an escape from their true impact.\n\nAccording to Zapffe, depressive disorders are often \"messages from a deeper, more immediate sense of life, bitter fruits of a geniality of thought\".<ref name=\"autoname3\" /> Some studies seem to confirm this, it is said about the phenomenon of [[depressive realism]], and Colin Feltham writes about antinatalism as one of its possible consequences.<ref>C. Feltham, ''Depressive Realism: Interdisciplinary perspectives'', Abingdon: Routledge, 2016.</ref>\n\nDavid Benatar citing numerous studies lists three phenomena described by psychologists, which, according to him, are responsible for making our self-assessments about the quality of our lives unreliable:\n* [[Optimism bias|Tendency towards optimism]] (or [[Pollyanna principle]]) \u2013 we have a positively distorted picture of our lives in the past, present and future.\n* Adaptation (or accommodation, habituation) \u2013 we adapt to negative situations and adjust our expectations accordingly.\n* Comparison \u2013 for our self-assessments about the quality of our lives, more important than how our lives go is how our they go in comparison with the lives of others. One of the effects of this is that negative aspects of life that affect everyone are not taken into account when assessing our own well-being. We are also more likely to compare ourselves with those who are worse off than those who are better off.\n\nBenatar concludes:\n\n{{quote|The above psychological phenomena are unsurprising from an evolutionary perspective. They militate against suicide and in favour of reproduction. If our lives are quite as bad as I shall still suggest they are, and if people were prone to see this true quality of their lives for what it is, they might be much more inclined to kill themselves, or at least not to produce more such lives. Pessimism, then, tends not to be naturally selected.<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 64\u201369.</ref>}}\n\n[[Thomas Ligotti]] draws attention to the similarity between Zapffe's philosophy and [[terror management theory]]. Terror management theory argues that humans are equipped with unique cognitive abilities beyond what is necessary for survival, which includes symbolic thinking, extensive self-consciousness and perception of themselves as temporal beings aware of the finitude of their existence. The desire to live alongside our awareness of the inevitability of death triggers terror in us. Opposition to this fear is among our primary motivations. To escape it, we build defensive structures around ourselves to ensure our symbolic or literal immortality, to feel like valuable members of a meaningful universe, and to focus on protecting ourselves from immediate external threats.<ref>T. Ligotti, ''The Conspiracy against the Human Race: A Contrivance of Horror'', New York: Hippocampus Press, 2010, pp. 112\u2013113.</ref>\n\n== Abortion ==\n\nAntinatalism can lead to a particular position on the morality of [[abortion]].\n\nAccording to David Benatar, one comes into existence in the morally relevant sense when consciousness arises, when a fetus becomes sentient, and up until that time an abortion is moral, whereas continued pregnancy would be immoral. Benatar refers to [[electroencephalography|EEG]] brain studies and studies on [[prenatal perception|the pain perception of the fetus]], which states that fetal consciousness arises no earlier than between twenty-eight and thirty weeks of pregnancy, before which it is incapable of feeling pain.<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 132\u2013162.</ref> Contrary to that, the latest report from the [[Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists]] showed that the fetus gains consciousness no earlier than week twenty-four of the pregnancy.<ref>[https://www.rcog.org.uk/globalassets/documents/guidelines/rcogfetalawarenesswpr0610.pdf] Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists, ''Fetal Awareness \u2013 Review of Research and Recommendations for Practice'', London: RCOG Press, 2010.</ref> Some assumptions of this report regarding sentience of the fetus after the second trimester were criticized.<ref>[http://fn.bmj.com/content/96/4/F236.long] M. W. Platt, ''Fetal awareness and fetal pain: the Emperor's new clothes'', ''Archives of Disease in Childhood'', 2011, volume 96, issue 4.</ref> In a similar way argues Karim Akerma. He distinguishes between organisms that do not have mental properties and living beings that have mental properties. According to his view, which he calls the mentalistic view, a living being begins to exist when an organism (or another entity) produces a simple form of consciousness for the first time.<ref>K. Akerma, ''Lebensende und Lebensbeginn: Philosophische Implikationen und mentalistische Begr\u00fcndung des Hirn-Todeskriterium'', Lit: Hamburg 2006.</ref><ref>K. Akerma, ''Antinatalismus...'' op. cit., p. 404.</ref>\n\nJulio Cabrera believes that the moral problem of abortion is totally different from the problem of abstention of procreation, because in the case of abortion, there is no longer a non-being, but an already existing being \u2013 the most helpless and defenceless of the parties involved, that someday will have the autonomy to decide, and we cannot decide for them. From the point of view of Cabrera's negative ethics, abortion is immoral for similar reasons as procreation. For Cabrera, the exception in which abortion is morally justified are cases of irreversible illness of the foetus (or some serious \"social illnesses\" like [[Spanish colonization of the Americas|American conquest]] or [[Nazism]]), according to him in such cases we are clearly thinking about the unborn, and not simply of our own interests. In addition, Cabrera believes that under certain circumstances, it is legitimate and comprehensible to commit unethical actions, for example, abortion is a legitimate and comprehensible, when the mother's life is at risk.<ref>[http://repositorio.unb.br/bitstream/10482/15274/1/LIVRO_PorqueTeAmo.pdf] J. Cabrera, T. Lenharo di Santis, op. cit, pp. 68\u201369, 77.</ref><ref>J.Cabrera, ''Discomfort'', op. cit., pp. 208\u2013233.</ref>\n\n== Non-human animals ==\n\nSome antinatalists recognize the procreation of non-human sentient animals as morally bad and sterilization as morally good in their case. Karim Akerma defines antinatalism, that includes non-human sentient animals, as universal antinatalism<ref>K. Akerma, ''Antinatalismus...'' op. cit., pp. 100\u2013101.</ref> and he assumes such a position himself:\n\n{{quote|By sterilising animals, we can free them from being slaves to their instincts and from bringing more and more captive animals into the cycle of being born, contracting parasites, ageing, falling ill and dying; eating and being eaten.<ref>[https://www.pro-iure-animalis.de/dokumente/manifest_antinatalismus.pdf] K. Akerma, ''Manifest zum antinatalismus. Zur Ethik des Antinatalismus. F\u00fcr Nachkommenlosigkeit bei Mensch und Tier'', ''Pro iure animalis'', July 2014. [http://akerma.de/Antinatalist%20Manifesto_Karim%20Akerma.pdf] English translation.</ref>|sign=|source=}}\n\nDavid Benatar emphasizes that his asymmetry applies to all sentient beings, and mentions that humans play a role in deciding how many animals there will be: humans breed other species of animals and are able to sterilize other species of animals.<ref>D. Benatar, ''Better...'', op. cit., pp. 2\u20133 (introduction), 163.</ref>\n\nMagnus Vinding argues that the life of wild animals in their natural environment is generally [[Wild animal suffering|very bad]]. He draws attention to phenomena such as dying before adulthood, starvation, diseases, [[parasites]], [[infanticide]], [[predation]] and being eaten alive. He cites research on what animal life looks like in the wild. One of eight male lion cubs survives into adulthood. Others die as a result of starvation, disease and often fall victims to the teeth and claws of other lions. Attaining adulthood is much rarer for fish. Only one in a hundred male chinook salmon survive into adulthood. Vinding is of the opinion that if human lives and the survival of human children looked like this, current human values would disallow procreation; however, this is not possible when it comes to non-human animals, who are guided by instinct. He takes the view that even if one does not agree that procreation is always morally bad, one should recognize procreation in wildlife as morally bad and something that ought to be prevented (at least in theory, not necessarily in practice). He maintains that non-intervention cannot be defended if we reject [[speciesism]] and that we should reject the unjustifiable [[Appeal to nature|dogma]] stating that what is happening in nature is what should be happening in nature.\n\n{{quote|We cannot allow ourselves to spuriously rationalize away the suffering that takes place in nature, and to forget the victims of the horrors of nature merely because that reality does not fit into our convenient moral theories, theories that ultimately just serve to make us feel consistent and good about ourselves in the face of an incomprehensibly bad reality.<ref>[https://www.smashwords.com/extreader/read/624122/1/the-speciesism-of-leaving-nature-alone-and-the-theoretical-c] M. Vinding, ''The Speciesism of Leaving Nature Alone, and the Theoretical Case for \"Wildlife Anti-Natalism\"'', 2017, ''Apeiron'', 8, pp. 169\u2013183.</ref>}}\n\n==Criticism==\n\nCriticism of antinatalism may come from views that see positive value in bringing humans into existence.<ref>D. Benatar, D. Wasserman, ''Debating...'', op. cit., pp. 133\u2013259.</ref> Results of surveys on subjective [[life satisfaction]], which show a vast surplus of happy people, could suggest that the overall benefit of procreation is greater than the harm and that therefore procreation is morally justified.<ref name=\"autoname4\" /> David Wasserman in his criticism of antinatalism, criticizes, among other things, David Benatar's arguments and the consent argument.<ref>D. Benatar, D. Wasserman, ''Debating...'', op. cit., pp. 148\u2013181.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Audianism]]\n* [[Borborites]]\n* [[Human population planning]]\n* [[Pessimism#Philosophical pessimism|Philosophical pessimism]]\n* [[Priscillianism]]\n* [[Voluntary childlessness]]{{div col end}}\n\n== Notes ==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{wikiquote|Antinatalism}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m7a04MAX2Cg Interview with David Benatar for Cape Talk on Radio 702, about ''Better Never to Have Been'', 2009]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V6DiB3OtFu4 Julio Cabrera's conference ''Birth as a bioethical problem: first steps towards a radical bioethics'' at the University of Bras\u00edlia, 2018]\n* [http://www.ligotti.net/showthread.php?p=93087 ''Antinatalism \u2013 list of books, articles and quotes'']\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-49298720 ''Anti-natalists: The people who want you to stop having babies''],\u00a0''BBC'', August 13, 2019\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/anti-natalists-childfree-population-climate-change ''I wish I'd never been born: the rise of the anti-natalists''], ''The Guardian'', November 14, 2019\n\n[[Category:Antinatalism]]\n[[Category:Bioethics]]\n[[Category:Ethical theories]]\n[[Category:Philosophy of biology]]\n", "name_user": "Sirhu", "label": "safe", "comment": "Restoring older description of \"moral impediment\". This is the exact same description Cabrera uses and can prevent someone from misunderstanding that \"moral impediment\" means that human beings cannot act morally under any circumstance.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antinatalism"}
{"title_page": "Cauchy boundary condition", "text_new": "In [[mathematics]], a '''Cauchy''' ({{IPA-fr|ko\u0283i|lang}}) '''[[Boundary value problem#Boundary value conditions|boundary condition]]''' augments an [[ordinary differential equation]] or a [[partial differential equation]] with conditions that the solution must satisfy on the boundary; ideally so to ensure that a unique solution exists. A Cauchy boundary condition specifies both the function value and [[normal derivative]] on the [[Boundary (topology)|boundary]] of the [[domain (mathematical analysis)|domain]]. This corresponds to imposing both a [[Dirichlet boundary condition|Dirichlet]] and a [[Neumann boundary condition]]. It is named after the prolific 19th-century French mathematical analyst [[Augustin Louis Cauchy]].\n\n==Second-order ordinary differential equations==\n\nCauchy boundary conditions are simple and common in second-order [[ordinary differential equations]],\n\n:<math>y''(s) = f\\big(y(s), y'(s), s\\big),</math>\n\nwhere, in order to ensure that a unique solution <math>y(s)</math> exists, one may specify the value of the function <math>y</math> and the value of the derivative <math>y'</math> at a given point <math>s=a</math>, i.e.,\n\n:<math>y(a) = \\alpha,</math>\n\nand\n\n:<math>y'(a) = \\beta,</math>\n\nwhere <math>a</math> is a boundary or initial point. Since the parameter <math>s</math> is usually time, Cauchy conditions can also be called ''initial value conditions'' or ''initial value data'' or simply ''Cauchy data''. An example of such a situation is Newton's laws of motion, where the acceleration <math>y''</math> depends on position <math>y</math>, velocity <math>y'</math>, and the time <math>s</math>; here, Cauchy data corresponds to knowing the initial position and velocity.\n\n==Partial differential equations==\n\nFor partial differential equations, Cauchy boundary conditions specify both the function and the normal derivative on the boundary. To make things simple and concrete, consider a second-order differential equation in the plane\n\n:<math>A(x,y) \\psi_{xx} + B(x,y) \\psi_{xy} + C(x,y) \\psi_{yy} = F(x,y,\\psi,\\psi_x,\\psi_y),</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\psi(x,y)</math> is the unknown solution, <math>\\psi_x</math> denotes derivative of <math>\\psi</math> with respect to <math>x</math> etc. The functions <math>A, B, C, F</math> specify the problem.\n\nWe now seek a <math>\\psi</math> that satisfies the partial differential equation in a domain <math>\\Omega</math>, which is a subset of the <math>xy</math> plane, and such that the Cauchy boundary conditions\n\n:<math>\\psi(x,y) = \\alpha(x,y), \\quad \\mathbf{n} \\cdot \\nabla\\psi = \\beta(x,y)</math>\n\nhold for all boundary points <math>(x,y) \\in \\partial\\Omega</math>. Here <math>\\mathbf{n} \\cdot \\nabla\\psi</math> is the derivative in the direction of the normal to the boundary. The functions <math>\\alpha</math> and <math>\\beta</math> are the Cauchy data.\n\nNotice the difference between a Cauchy boundary condition and a [[Robin boundary condition]]. In the former, we specify both the function and the normal derivative. In the latter, we specify a weighted average of the two.\n\nWe would like boundary conditions to ensure that exactly one (unique) solution exists, but for second-order partial differential equations, it is not as simple to guarantee existence and uniqueness as it is for ordinary differential equations. Cauchy data are most immediately relevant for [[hyperbolic partial differential equation|hyperbolic]] problems (for example, the [[wave equation]]) on open domains (for example, the half plane).<ref name=hobson>{{cite book|last1=Riley|first1=K. F.|last2=Hobson|first2=M. P.|last3=Bence|first3=S. J.|title=Mathematical methods for physics and engineering|url=https://archive.org/details/mathematicalmeth00rile|url-access=registration|isbn=978-0-521-67971-8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mathematicalmeth00rile/page/705 705]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dirichlet boundary condition]]\n*[[Mixed boundary condition]]\n*[[Neumann boundary condition]]\n*[[Robin boundary condition]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cauchy Boundary Condition}}\n[[Category:Boundary conditions]]\n", "text_old": "In [[mathematics]], a '''Cauchy''' ({{IPA-fr|ko\u0283i|lang}}) '''[[Boundary value problem#Boundary value conditions|boundary condition]]''' augments an [[ordinary differential equation]] or a [[partial differential equation]] with conditions that the solution must satisfy on the boundary; ideally so to ensure that a unique solution exists. A Cauchy boundary condition specifies both the function value and [[normal derivative]] on the [[Boundary (topology)|boundary]] of the [[domain (mathematics)|domain]]. This corresponds to imposing both a [[Dirichlet boundary condition|Dirichlet]] and a [[Neumann boundary condition]]. It is named after the prolific 19th-century French mathematical analyst [[Augustin Louis Cauchy]].\n\n==Second-order ordinary differential equations==\n\nCauchy boundary conditions are simple and common in second-order [[ordinary differential equations]],\n\n:<math>y''(s) = f\\big(y(s), y'(s), s\\big),</math>\n\nwhere, in order to ensure that a unique solution <math>y(s)</math> exists, one may specify the value of the function <math>y</math> and the value of the derivative <math>y'</math> at a given point <math>s=a</math>, i.e.,\n\n:<math>y(a) = \\alpha,</math>\n\nand\n\n:<math>y'(a) = \\beta,</math>\n\nwhere <math>a</math> is a boundary or initial point. Since the parameter <math>s</math> is usually time, Cauchy conditions can also be called ''initial value conditions'' or ''initial value data'' or simply ''Cauchy data''. An example of such a situation is Newton's laws of motion, where the acceleration <math>y''</math> depends on position <math>y</math>, velocity <math>y'</math>, and the time <math>s</math>; here, Cauchy data corresponds to knowing the initial position and velocity.\n\n==Partial differential equations==\n\nFor partial differential equations, Cauchy boundary conditions specify both the function and the normal derivative on the boundary. To make things simple and concrete, consider a second-order differential equation in the plane\n\n:<math>A(x,y) \\psi_{xx} + B(x,y) \\psi_{xy} + C(x,y) \\psi_{yy} = F(x,y,\\psi,\\psi_x,\\psi_y),</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\psi(x,y)</math> is the unknown solution, <math>\\psi_x</math> denotes derivative of <math>\\psi</math> with respect to <math>x</math> etc. The functions <math>A, B, C, F</math> specify the problem.\n\nWe now seek a <math>\\psi</math> that satisfies the partial differential equation in a domain <math>\\Omega</math>, which is a subset of the <math>xy</math> plane, and such that the Cauchy boundary conditions\n\n:<math>\\psi(x,y) = \\alpha(x,y), \\quad \\mathbf{n} \\cdot \\nabla\\psi = \\beta(x,y)</math>\n\nhold for all boundary points <math>(x,y) \\in \\partial\\Omega</math>. Here <math>\\mathbf{n} \\cdot \\nabla\\psi</math> is the derivative in the direction of the normal to the boundary. The functions <math>\\alpha</math> and <math>\\beta</math> are the Cauchy data.\n\nNotice the difference between a Cauchy boundary condition and a [[Robin boundary condition]]. In the former, we specify both the function and the normal derivative. In the latter, we specify a weighted average of the two.\n\nWe would like boundary conditions to ensure that exactly one (unique) solution exists, but for second-order partial differential equations, it is not as simple to guarantee existence and uniqueness as it is for ordinary differential equations. Cauchy data are most immediately relevant for [[hyperbolic partial differential equation|hyperbolic]] problems (for example, the [[wave equation]]) on open domains (for example, the half plane).<ref name=hobson>{{cite book|last1=Riley|first1=K. F.|last2=Hobson|first2=M. P.|last3=Bence|first3=S. J.|title=Mathematical methods for physics and engineering|url=https://archive.org/details/mathematicalmeth00rile|url-access=registration|isbn=978-0-521-67971-8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mathematicalmeth00rile/page/705 705]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dirichlet boundary condition]]\n*[[Mixed boundary condition]]\n*[[Neumann boundary condition]]\n*[[Robin boundary condition]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cauchy Boundary Condition}}\n[[Category:Boundary conditions]]\n", "name_user": "Tea2min", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix link.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cauchy_boundary_condition"}
{"title_page": "Richard Madden", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Richard Robert Madden}}\n{{short description|Scottish film and television actor}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Richard Madden\n| image              = [[File:Richard Madden Smiling 1.jpg|thumb|]]\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Madden at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1986|6|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Elderslie]], [[Renfrewshire]], Scotland\n| nationality        = Scottish\n| alma_mater         = [[Royal Conservatoire of Scotland]]\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 1999\u2013present\n| partner            = \n| website            = \n}}\n'''Richard Madden''' (born 18 June 1986) is a Scottish film and television actor. Born and raised in [[Renfrewshire]] near [[Glasgow]], Madden rose to prominence in 2011 for his portrayal of [[Robb Stark]] in the first three seasons of [[HBO]]'s fantasy drama ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', for which he received the [[Screen International|Screen International Award for Star of Tomorrow]]. In 2018, he gained acclaim for his performance as a war veteran and Principal Protection Officer in the [[BBC]] thriller series ''[[Bodyguard (British TV series)|Bodyguard]]'', for which he won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama]] and was also nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Primetime Emmy Award For Outstanding Lead Actor In A Drama Series]].\n\nMadden made his screen debut as a child actor and later began performing on stage whilst a student at the [[Royal Conservatoire of Scotland]]. In 2007, he toured with [[Shakespeare's Globe]] company as [[Romeo]] in ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'', a role he reprised in the [[West End theatre|West End]] in 2016. His other television and film credits include the lead role of [[Cosimo de' Medici]] in the first season of the historical fiction series ''[[Medici (TV series)|Medici]]'' (2016), [[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Prince Charming|Prince Kit]] in [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]'s live-action ''[[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|Cinderella]]'' (2015), [[John Reid (music manager)|John Reid]] in the biopic ''[[Rocketman (film)|Rocketman]]'' (2019), and a lieutenant in the epic war film ''[[1917 (2019 film)|1917]]'' (2019).\n\n==Life and career==\n===1986\u20132010: Early life and work===\nMadden was born on 18 June 1986 in [[Elderslie]], [[Renfrewshire]], outside the city of [[Glasgow]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/06/18/Famous-birthdays-for-June-18-Lou-Brock-Carol-Kane/3041560703882/|website=[[United Press International]]|title=Famous birthdays for June 18: Lou Brock, Carol Kane|date=18 June 2019|access-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619140329/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/06/18/Famous-birthdays-for-June-18-Lou-Brock-Carol-Kane/3041560703882/|archive-date=19 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/17378326.richard-madden-wins-best-drama-performance-at-national-television-awards/|website=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|title=Richard Madden wins best drama performance at National Television Awards|last=Duffy|first=Elle|date=23 January 2019|access-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203235530/https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/17378326.richard-madden-wins-best-drama-performance-at-national-television-awards/|archive-date=3 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-45665620|title=The Sunday night drama plugging the gap left by Bodyguard|last=Rutherford|first=Nichola|website=[[BBC Online]]|date=29 September 2018|access-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426125712/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-45665620|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> where he was also raised alongside his two sisters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marieclaire.co.uk/entertainment/richard-madden-609357|date=5 September 2018|access-date=4 April 2020|last=Pavia|first=Lucy|title=Bodyguard's Richard Madden on shyness, Game of Thrones and his 'relentless' new show|website=[[Marie Claire]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2019/02/breakout-stars-stand-out-in-spring-style|title=Rowan Blanchard, Dree Hemingway, Jeremy O. Harris, and Seven More Breakout Stars Stand Out in Spring Style|last=Hennemuth|first=Britt|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=28 February 2019|access-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404060333/https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2019/02/breakout-stars-stand-out-in-spring-style|archive-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> His mother, Pat, is a primary school teacher, and his father, Richard, worked as a firefighter.<ref name=les1411>{{cite news | url = http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/lifestyle/article-23937373-game-of-thrones-is-good-news-for-brit-stars.do | title = Game of Thrones is good news for Brit stars | first = Hannah | last = Nathanson |date = 1 April 2011 | website = [[The Evening Standard]] | accessdate = 1 April 2011|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110404202243/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/lifestyle/article-23937373-game-of-thrones-is-good-news-for-brit-stars.do |archive-date=4 April 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Guard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/may/04/richard-madden-bodyguard-rocketman-bullies-inner-fat-lad-miranda-sawyer|title=Richard Madden: 'I don't like the look of me in the mirror'|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 May 2019|last=Sawyer|first=Miranda|access-date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107024439/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/may/04/richard-madden-bodyguard-rocketman-bullies-inner-fat-lad-miranda-sawyer|archive-date=7 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> At age 11, Madden joined [[PACE Youth Theatre]] to help overcome his shyness.<ref name=les1411/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/pace-congratulates-golden-star-richard-13827617|title=PACE congratulates golden star Richard Madden|first=Gary|last=Armstrong|date=8 January 2019|website=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|The Daily Record]]|access-date=30 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730201746/https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/pace-congratulates-golden-star-richard-13827617|archive-date=30 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He was soon cast in his first role as young Andy in the [[Complicity (film)|film adaptation]] of [[Iain Banks]]' ''[[Complicity (novel)|Complicity]]'',<ref name=\"GQ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/richard-madden-james-bond-interview|title=Richard Madden on Bond, bullying and Bodyguard. The GQ interview|first=Stuart|last=McGurk|date=30 November 2018|magazine=[[GQ]]|access-date=7 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107181132/https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/richard-madden-james-bond-interview|archive-date=7 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> which was released in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2000/film/reviews/complicity-1117787770/|title=Complicity|date=7 August 2000|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Elley|first=Derek|access-date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409123047/http://variety.com/2000/film/reviews/complicity-1117787770/|archive-date=9 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He was then cast in the lead role of Sebastian in the children's television series ''[[Barmy Aunt Boomerang]]'',<ref name=\"scotsman1\">{{cite news |url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/performing-arts/Up-and-Coming-Richard-Madden.5088603.jp |title=Up and Coming: Richard Madden \u2013 Young man on a role |last=Mansfield |first=Susan |date=21 March 2009 |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812061342/http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/performing-arts/Up-and-Coming-Richard-Madden.5088603.jp |archive-date=12 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which aired from 1999 until 2000.<ref name=\"heraldscotland1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/less-room-for-doom-in-the-great-outdoors-1.840149 |title=Less room for doom in the great outdoors |last=Cooper |first=Neil |date=12 June 2007 |newspaper=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150628020152/http://www.heraldscotland.com/less-room-for-doom-in-the-great-outdoors-1.840149 |archive-date=28 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Madden later stated that he experienced bullying following his performance in ''Complicity'', especially in high school.<ref name=\"GQ\"/>\n\nHe later attended the [[Royal Conservatoire of Scotland]], formerly the Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama, in Glasgow, graduating in 2007.<ref name=\"scotsman1\"/><ref name=\"heraldscotland1\"/> He worked with [[The Arches (Glasgow)|The Arches]] and the Glasgow Repertory Company during his studies; he also performed in [[Franz Xaver Kroetz]]'s play ''Tom Fool'' at the [[Citizens Theatre]]. After receiving positive reviews, the ''Tom Fool'' production transferred to London, where Madden was spotted by a team from [[Shakespeare's Globe]].<ref name=\"heraldscotland1\"/> In his final year at the conservatoire, he was cast as [[Romeo]] in a production of ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'' at the modern [[Globe Theatre]] in London, after which the company embarked on a tour of the production during the summer of 2007.<ref name=\"heraldscotland1\"/><ref name=\"theindependent\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/romeo-and-juliet-dulwich-park-london-463880.html |title=Romeo and Juliet, Dulwich Park, London |last=Taylor |first=Paul |date=5 September 2007 |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111025722/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/romeo-and-juliet-dulwich-park-london-463880.html |archive-date=11 November 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In her review of the production, Susan Elkin of ''[[The Stage]]'' highlighted Madden's \"gravelly Glaswegian, almost childlike Romeo\".<ref name=\"thestage\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/17422/romeo-and-juliet |title=Reviews: Romeo and Juliet |last=Elkin |first=Susan |date=16 July 2007 |work=[[The Stage]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611141314/http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/17422/romeo-and-juliet |archive-date=11 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe played Callum McGregor in the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]'s production of [[Malorie Blackman]]'s ''[[Noughts & Crosses (novel series)|Noughts & Crosses]]'' in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2007/dec/07/theatre|last=Billington|first=Michael|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=7 December 2007|title=Theatre review: Noughts and Crosses / Civic Hall, Stratford-on-Avon|access-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528231201/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2007/dec/07/theatre|archive-date=28 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He then starred as Mark McNulty in the [[National Theatre of Scotland]]'s production of ''[[Be Near Me]]'' in 2009, during which Warwick Thompson of ''[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]'' noted Madden's performance to be \"especially good\".<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=at.CnEGmT0Tk&refer=muse |title=Richard Dreyfuss, Sporting Earpiece, Triumphs in New Play |last=Thompson |first=Warwick |date=29 January 2009 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105013020/https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=at.CnEGmT0Tk&refer=muse |archive-date=5 November 2012}}</ref> Susan Mansfield of ''[[The Scotsman]]'' reported that Madden has caught the eye of critics for his work and reported additional positive reviews of his work by ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' and ''[[The Observer]].''<ref name=\"scotsman1\"/> He later gained the lead role of Dean McKenzie in the 2009 [[BBC]] comedy-drama series ''[[Hope Springs (TV series)|Hope Springs]]'',<ref name=\"scotsman1\"/> followed by his roles as Ripley in the 2010 film ''[[Chatroom (film)|Chatroom]]'',<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2010/film/markets-festivals/chatroom-1117942758/ |title=Reviews: Chatroom |last=Felperin |first=Leslie|date=14 May 2010 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=26 October 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421174208/https://variety.com/2010/film/markets-festivals/chatroom-1117942758/ |archive-date=21 April 2016}}</ref> and as [[Theatre of Hate]] singer [[Kirk Brandon]] in the 2010 film ''[[Worried About the Boy]]''.<ref name=\"newstatesman\">{{cite news |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/television/2010/05/boy-george-strange-song |title=Worried About the Boy |last=Cooke |first=Rachel |date=21 May 2010 |work=[[New Statesman]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305033417/http://www.newstatesman.com/television/2010/05/boy-george-strange-song |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2011\u2013present: Breakthrough===\n[[File:Richard Madden by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|Madden at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]]]\nMadden starred as [[Robb Stark]] in the [[HBO]] series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', based upon the series of novels titled ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'' by [[George R. R. Martin]], from 2011 to 2013.<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter\">{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3iebbbd387ec9a77d4309a5c3b4bb8e30e |title=HBO appoints subjects to 'Thrones' |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=20 August 2009 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110104028/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3iebbbd387ec9a77d4309a5c3b4bb8e30e |archivedate=10 January 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"iftn\">{{cite news |url=http://www.iftn.ie/?act1=record&aid=73&rid=4282905&tpl=archnewshome&only=1&force=1 |title=HBO Greenlights Northern Ireland Epic 'Game of Thrones' |date=4 March 2010 |work=[[Irish Film and Television Network]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306072036/http://iftn.ie/?act1=record&aid=73&force=1&only=1&rid=4282905&tpl=archnewshome |archive-date=6 March 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Not\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-45393546|title=Richard Madden 'not paid much' in Game of Thrones|date=3 September 2018|website=[[BBC Online]]|language=en-GB|access-date=3 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903193332/https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-45393546|archive-date=3 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Madden's performance in the series propelled him to prominence.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/31/movies/richard-madden-rocketman.html|title=It's Going Great for Richard Madden. That's What Worries Him|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=31 May 2019|last=Buchanan|first=Kyle|access-date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214221202/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/31/movies/richard-madden-rocketman.html|archive-date=14 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/richard-madden-offered-bond-role-2389822|website=[[NME]]|title=Is Richard Madden about to be offered the Bond role?|last=Matheson|first=Anna|date=14 October 2018|access-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404060930/https://www.nme.com/news/richard-madden-offered-bond-role-2389822|archive-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> During this period, Madden also starred in the [[Channel 4]] comedy-drama series ''[[Sirens (2011 TV series)|Sirens]]'' and in the BBC drama series ''[[Birdsong (TV series)|Birdsong]]''.<ref name=\"Birdsong\">{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/redeye-richard-madden-game-of-thrones-interview-tv-20120422-story.html|title=Richard Madden talks 1st love on 'Game of Thrones'|website=[[The Chicago Tribune]]|date=22 April 2012|last=Wagner|first=Curt|access-date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624162403/https://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/redeye-richard-madden-game-of-thrones-interview-tv-20120422-story.html|archive-date=24 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Madden first obtained his [[Screen Actors Guild]] (SAG) card for the 2014 miniseries ''[[Klondike (miniseries)|Klondike]]'', in which he played Bill Haskell.<ref name=TVGuide>{{cite magazine| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=How Did You Get Your SAG-AFTRA Card?|magazine=[[TV Guide]]|date=13 January 2014|page=10}}</ref><ref name=\"Klondike\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2014/01/17/richard-madden-klondike-game-thrones/|title=Richard Madden on his lack of 'Klondike' headwear \u2013 LISTEN!|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Bierly|first=Mandy|date=17 January 2014|access-date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722050954/http://ew.com/article/2014/01/17/richard-madden-klondike-game-thrones/|archive-date=22 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He then portrayed the prince in the live action Disney film ''[[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|Cinderella]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Schillaci|first=Sophie|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cinderella-game-thrones-richard-madden-519557|title=Disney Casts 'Game of Thrones' Actor as 'Cinderella's' Prince|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=8 May 2013|access-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190625215520/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cinderella-game-thrones-richard-madden-519557|archive-date=25 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> which was released in March 2015.<ref name=\"Cind\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a633497/richard-madden-jokes-about-cinderella-a-happy-ending-is-nice/|title=Richard Madden jokes about Cinderella: 'A happy ending is nice'|last=Harp|first=Justin|date=4 March 2015|access-date=4 April 2020|website=[[Digital Spy]]|url-status=live|archive-date=4 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404061305/https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a633497/richard-madden-jokes-about-cinderella-a-happy-ending-is-nice/}}</ref> The film became a commercial and critical success, receiving positive reviews and grossing over $542 million.<ref name=\"Barnes\">{{cite web|last=Barnes|first=Brooks|title=Forget the Ball, ''Cinderella'' Is the Belle of the Box Office|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=15 March 2015|accessdate=7 January 2020|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/15/forget-the-ball-cinderella-is-the-belle-of-the-box-office/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908065415/http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/15/forget-the-ball-cinderella-is-the-belle-of-the-box-office/|archive-date=8 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/cinderella-movie-profit-2015-box-office-disney-1201724740/|title=No. 8 'Cinderella' \u2013 2015 Most Valuable Movie Blockbuster Tournament|last=Fleming|first=Mike Jr.|date=23 March 2016|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191207160139/https://deadline.com/2016/03/cinderella-movie-profit-2015-box-office-disney-1201724740/|archive-date=7 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBetween 12 May and 13 August 2016, Madden appeared on stage in London's [[West End theatre|West End]] playing the part of Romeo in ''Romeo and Juliet'', where he was reunited with his ''Cinderella'' co-star [[Lily James]], who played Juliet, and director [[Kenneth Branagh]].<ref name=\"LTD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.londontheatredirect.com/news/5647/stars-on-stage-this-years-big-stars-in-the-west-end.aspx|title=Stars On Stage: This Year's Big Stars In The West End|date=13 August 2015|first=Harry|last=Tennison|work=[[London Theatre Direct]]|access-date=26 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026222734/https://www.londontheatredirect.com/news/5647/stars-on-stage-this-years-big-stars-in-the-west-end.aspx|archive-date=26 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Madden was replaced as Romeo in July 2016 after suffering an ankle injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2016/richard-madden-withdraws-from-romeo-and-juliet/|title=Richard Madden withdraws from Romeo and Juliet following medical advice|work=[[The Stage]]|date=4 August 2016|first=Matthew|last=Hemley|access-date=29 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806130607/https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2016/richard-madden-withdraws-from-romeo-and-juliet/|archive-date=6 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He then played the leading role of [[Cosimo de' Medici]], the son of the founder of the [[Medici Bank]] during the [[Italian Renaissance]], in the first season of the Italian-British television drama series, ''[[Medici (TV series)|Medici]]'', subtitled ''Masters of Florence''.<ref name=\"Medici\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/richard-madden-playing-a-medici-938717|title=Richard Madden on Playing a Medici, New Show 'Oasis' and Those 'Game of Thrones' Rumors (Q&A)|last=Anderson|first=Ariston|date=17 October 2016|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210121725/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/richard-madden-playing-a-medici-938717|archive-date=10 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the same year, he portrayed American pickpocket Michael Mason in the 2016 action film ''[[Bastille Day (2016 film)|Bastille Day]]'', starring alongside [[Idris Elba]].<ref name=\"Bastille\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/richard-madden-bastille-day-casting-1201319740/|title='Game of Thrones' Star Richard Madden Joins Idris Elba in 'Bastille Day' (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=2 October 2014|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=28 June 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628154440/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/richard-madden-bastille-day-casting-1201319740/|archive-date=28 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Madden garnered acclaim and recognition for his portrayal of Sergeant David Budd, a war veteran and Principal Protection Officer, in the BBC thriller series ''[[Bodyguard (British TV series)|Bodyguard]]''.<ref name=\"BG\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/bodyguard-richard-madden-jed-mercurio-netflix-emmys-interview-1202629351/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|title=Richard Madden Discusses His Transition From The \"Insularity And Paranoia\" Of 'Bodyguard' To Elton John Biopic 'Rocketman'|last=Wise|first=Damon|date=19 June 2019|access-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810072808/https://deadline.com/2019/06/bodyguard-richard-madden-jed-mercurio-netflix-emmys-interview-1202629351/|archive-date=10 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/0/bodyguard-elton-johns-lover-richard-maddens-next-role/|title=From Bodyguard to Elton John's lover: Richard Madden's surprising next role|date=25 September 2018|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001083445/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/0/bodyguard-elton-johns-lover-richard-maddens-next-role/|archive-date=1 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> After achieving high levels of popularity in the UK, the show was released to a worldwide audience on [[Netflix]] in October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/sep/18/netflix-picks-up-bbc-bodyguard-and-itv-cashes-in|title=Netflix picks up BBC's Bodyguard \u2013 and ITV cashes in|first=Jim|last=Waterson|date=18 September 2018|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=18 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181218194804/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/sep/18/netflix-picks-up-bbc-bodyguard-and-itv-cashes-in|archive-date=18 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2018-12-18/bodyguard-netflix-season-1/|title=Bodyguard on Netflix: everything you need to know about the hit BBC TV series|first=James|last=Gill|date=18 December 2018|work=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=18 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181218193431/https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2018-12-18/bodyguard-netflix-season-1/|archive-date=18 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> His performance earned him a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama]].<ref name=\"GG\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-46747537|title=Golden Globes 2019: Olivia Colman, Ben Whishaw and Richard Madden win|date=7 January 2019|website=[[BBC Online]]|access-date=7 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107084959/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-46747537|archive-date=7 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The series went on to become the UK's most watched television drama since current records began.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/bodyguard-most-watched|title=BBC One's Bodyguard is the UK's most watched drama since current records began|date=23 October 2018|website=[[BBC Online]]|access-date=7 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107181847/https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/bodyguard-most-watched|archive-date=7 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Bodyguard'' was also nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]], however, critics and viewers alike expressed disappointment over the fact that Madden did not receive an Emmy nomination for his performance, deeming it a snub.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/biggest-emmy-snubs-surprises-2019-nominations-julia-roberts-big-bang-theory-schitts-creek-1202646686/|title=Emmy Snubs & Surprises: 'Big Bang Theory', Julia Roberts, & Richard Madden Left Out In The TV Academy Cold; 'Schitt's Creek' Strong|last=Patten|first=Dominic|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=16 July 2019|access-date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224132449/https://deadline.com/2019/07/biggest-emmy-snubs-surprises-2019-nominations-julia-roberts-big-bang-theory-schitts-creek-1202646686/|archive-date=24 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/awards/story/2019-07-16/richard-maddens-fans-are-none-too-pleased-about-his-emmys-snub|title=Richard Madden's fans are none too pleased about his Emmys snub|first=Michael|last=Ordo\u00f1a|date=16 August 2019|website=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=16 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815165035/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/awards/story/2019-07-16/richard-maddens-fans-are-none-too-pleased-about-his-emmys-snub|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/emmys/2019/07/16/emmy-nominations-snubs-2019/|title=Emmy nominations biggest snubs and surprises|first=Hibberd|last=James|date=16 July 2019|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215012733/https://ew.com/emmys/2019/07/16/emmy-nominations-snubs-2019/|archive-date=15 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following his performance in ''Bodyguard'', Madden starred in the [[Netflix]] romantic comedy film ''[[Ibiza (film)|Ibiza]]'' alongside [[Gillian Jacobs]], [[Vanessa Bayer]] and [[Phoebe Robinson]].<ref name=\"Ibiza\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/dj-david-budd-bodyguard-fans-need-watch-richard-maddens-netflix/|title=DJ David Budd: why Bodyguard fans need to watch Ibiza, Richard Madden's bangin' Netflix romcom|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=14 September 2018|last=Jones|first=Lucy|access-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010043518/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/dj-david-budd-bodyguard-fans-need-watch-richard-maddens-netflix/|archive-date=10 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Madden portrayed music manager [[John Reid (music manager)|John Reid]] in the [[Elton John]] biopic ''[[Rocketman (film)|Rocketman]]'', which was released in May,<ref name=\"Guard\"/> and appeared as a lieutenant in [[Sam Mendes]]' war film ''[[1917 (2019 film)|1917]]'', which was released in December.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/12/30/21021190/sam-mendes-interview-1917-one-shot|title=Why Sam Mendes made 1917 look like it was shot in a single, continuous take|date=30 December 2019|last=Wilkinson|first=Alissa|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108225906/https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/12/30/21021190/sam-mendes-interview-1917-one-shot|archive-date=8 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMadden will also star as [[Ikaris]] in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] film ''[[The Eternals (film)|The Eternals]]'', directed by [[Chlo\u00e9 Zhao]], which is scheduled for a February 2021 release.<ref name=\"Eternals\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/jan/02/first-transgender-marvel-superhero-coming-very-soon-kevin-feige|title=First transgender Marvel superhero coming 'very soon'|first=Shoard|last=Catherine|date=2 January 2020|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107031246/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/jan/02/first-transgender-marvel-superhero-coming-very-soon-kevin-feige|archive-date=7 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/box-office/disney-mulan-black-widow-release-dates-coronavirus-1203550173/|title='Black Widow,' 'Eternals,' 'Indiana Jones 5' and More Disney Films Get New Release Dates|last=Rubin|first=Rebecca|date=3 April 2020|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403231745/https://variety.com/2020/film/box-office/disney-mulan-black-widow-release-dates-coronavirus-1203550173/|archive-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> He has also been cast in a leading role in an upcoming [[Amazon Studios]] \"multi-series\" titled ''Citadel'', executive produced by [[Anthony and Joe Russo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/priyanka-chopra-jonas-richard-madden-to-star-in-citadel-amazons-russo-brothers-international-event-series-1202830243/|date=14 January 2020|last=Petski|first=Denise|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|title=Priyanka Chopra Jonas & Richard Madden To Star In 'Citadel', Amazon's Russo Brothers International Event Series|access-date=19 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115131048/https://deadline.com/2020/01/priyanka-chopra-jonas-richard-madden-to-star-in-citadel-amazons-russo-brothers-international-event-series-1202830243/|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\nMadden won Most Stylish Male at the Scottish Style Awards in October 2009 and was also named in ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''{{'}}s Hottest Stars for 2010.<ref name=\"scotsman2\">{{cite news |url=http://living.scotsman.com/scotland-on-sunday-eligibles-2010/Scotland39s-most-eligible-men-.6073719.jp |title=Scotland's most eligible men \u2013 #15: Richard Madden, 23, actor |date=16 February 2010 |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100222050645/http://living.scotsman.com/scotland-on-sunday-eligibles-2010/Scotland39s-most-eligible-men-.6073719.jp |archive-date=22 February 2010}}</ref> He was named one of [[Screen International]]'s Stars of Tomorrow in 2011.<ref name=\"Future\">{{cite web |url=http://www.screendaily.com/reports/stars-of-tomorrow/richard-madden/5029108.article |title=Screen stars of tomorrow: Richard Madden |work=[[Screen International]] |date=30 June 2011 |accessdate=29 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010225638/http://www.screendaily.com/reports/stars-of-tomorrow/richard-madden/5029108.article |archive-date=10 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019, Madden was recognised with the ''[[GQ]]'' Men of the Year Award for Hugo Boss Most Stylish Man.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gq-men-of-the-year-awards-winners-taron-egerton-richard-madden-andrew-scott-a9090391.html|title=GQ Men of the Year Awards: Taron Egerton, Richard Madden and Stormzy win top prizes|last=Barr|first=Sabrina|date=3 September 2019|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=8 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923160002/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gq-men-of-the-year-awards-winners-taron-egerton-richard-madden-andrew-scott-a9090391.html|archive-date=23 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He was also named one of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]] by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine in the same year.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kenneth|last=Branagh|title=Richard Madden|url=http://time.com/collection/100-most-influential-people-2019/5567867/richard-madden/|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=17 April 2019|accessdate=6 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206054912/https://time.com/collection/100-most-influential-people-2019/5567867/richard-madden/|archive-date=6 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMadden was previously in a relationship with English actress [[Jenna Coleman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-richard-madden-jenna-coleman-cinderella-premiere-20150302-story.html|website=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|title='Thrones' alum Richard Madden steps out with girlfriend at 'Cinderella' premiere'|last=Saad|first=Nardine|date=2 March 2015|access-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022134644/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-richard-madden-jenna-coleman-cinderella-premiere-20150302-story.html|archive-date=22 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2015/06/prince-harry-jenna-coleman-dating|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|title=Prince Harry Reportedly Has a New Love Interest, and You May Know Her from TV|last=Duboff|first=Josh|date=19 June 2015|access-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428191929/https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2015/06/prince-harry-jenna-coleman-dating|archive-date=28 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> As of May 2019, Madden split his time between his residence in London and Los Angeles.<ref name=\"Guard\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/richard-madden-james-bond|website=[[British Vogue]]|title=Richard Madden On Potentially Playing Second Fiddle To A Female Bond|last=Edwardes|first=Charlotte|date=4 May 2019|access-date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191010190329/https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/richard-madden-james-bond|archive-date=10 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> When asked about his private life during a ''[[New York Times]]'' interview, Madden stated: \"I just keep my personal life personal.\"<ref name=\"NYT\"/> In July 2019, he received an Honorary Doctorate of Drama from his alma mater, the Royal Conservatoire of Scotland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rcs.ac.uk/graduation/|title=Graduation \u2013 Royal Conservatoire of Scotland|first=Royal|last=Conservatoire|date=4 May 2019|work=[[Royal Conservatoire of Scotland]]|access-date=5 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730021654/https://www.rcs.ac.uk/graduation/|archive-date=30 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2000\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Complicity (film)|Complicity]]''\n| Young Andy\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"GQ\"/>\n|-\n| 2010\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Chatroom (film)|Chatroom]]''\n| Ripley Collins\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"variety\"/>\n|-\n| 2011\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Strays''\n| Elliot\n| Short film\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/dkz956/the-shooting-gallery--s4-e1-strays/|title=The Shooting Gallery|website=[[Radio Times]]|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[A Promise (2013 film)|A Promise]]''\n| Friedrich Zeitz\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/18/movies/a-promise-with-alan-rickman-and-rebecca-hall.html|title='A Promise,' With Alan Rickman and Rebecca Hall|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=17 April 2014|last=Holden|first=Stephen|access-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424165856/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/18/movies/a-promise-with-alan-rickman-and-rebecca-hall.html|archive-date=24 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|Cinderella]]''\n| [[List of Disney's Cinderella character