y:Scottish male voice actors]]\n", "name_user": "Mukund SB 99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor details.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Madden"}
{"title_page": "Sara Studebaker-Hall", "text_new": "{{short description|American biathlete}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2014}}\n\n'''Sara Studebaker-Hall''' (born October 7, 1984) is a retired [[Biathlon|biathlete]] from the [[United States]] who competed on the [[Biathlon World Cup|World Cup]] circuit from [[2009\u201310 Biathlon World Cup|2009]] to [[2013\u201314 Biathlon World Cup|2014]]. Born and raised in [[Boise, Idaho]], she has had multiple top 20 results and her best World Cup finishes are 14th in the sprint event at [[Presque Isle, Maine]] in February [[2010\u201311 Biathlon World Cup|2011]] and 15th in the sprint at [[Kontiolahti]], [[Finland]] in February [[2011\u201312 Biathlon World Cup|2012]].  She placed 17th in the individual race at the [[Biathlon World Championships 2011|2011 World Championships]] in [[Khanty-Mansiysk]], [[Russia]]. She was ranked 34th in the World Cup in the [[2010\u201311 Biathlon World Cup|2010\u201311]] season and 55th for [[2011\u201312 Biathlon World Cup|2011\u201312]].\n\nStudebaker, a member of the [[Biathlon at the 2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Winter Olympic]] team, placed 34th in the 15&nbsp;km individual at [[Whistler Olympic Park]], Canada.  She has been a member of the U.S. Biathlon Team since 2007, after her graduation from [[Dartmouth College]], where she captained the NCAA champion cross country ski team. Studebaker is a 2003 graduate of [[Boise High School]] and learned to ski at [[Bogus Basin]].\n\nStudebaker retired from the sport at the end of the 2013-14 season.<ref name=retirement>{{cite web |url=http://www5.biathlonworld.com/en/press_releases.html/do/detail?presse=2216 |title=Retiring from Biathlon; Part 2, the Women |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=29 April 2014 |website=[[International Biathlon Union]] |accessdate=23 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103161722/http://www5.biathlonworld.com/en/press_releases.html/do/detail?presse=2216 |archivedate=3 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 she married biathlete Zach Hall.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Blogspot|sarastudebaker|Official page}}\n*[http://www4.biathlonworld.com/en/athletes.html/do/showathlete?IBUId=BTUSA20710198401 IBU profile] \u2013 Sara Studebaker\n*{{USOPC profile|ST/Sara-Studebaker}}\n*{{SR/Olympics|st/sara-studebaker-1}}\n*[http://www.boiseweekly.com/boise/who-sara-studebaker/Content?oid=2690143 Boise Weekly.com] \u2013 Sara Studebaker\n*[http://i.nbcolympics.com/athletes/athlete=2613/index.html NBC Olympics] \u2013 Sara Studebaker\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Studebaker, Sara}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American female biathletes]]\n[[Category:Biathletes at the 2010 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Biathletes at the 2014 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic biathletes of the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-biathlon-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American biathlete}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2014}}\n\n'''Sara Studebaker-Hall''' (born October 7, 1984) is a retired [[Biathlon|biathlete]] from the [[United States]] who competed on the [[Biathlon World Cup|World Cup]] circuit from [[2009\u201310 Biathlon World Cup|2009]] to [[2013\u201314 Biathlon World Cup|2014]]. Born and raised in [[Boise, Idaho]], she has had multiple top 20 results and her best World Cup finishes are 14th in the sprint event at [[Presque Isle, Maine]] in February [[2010\u201311 Biathlon World Cup|2011]] and 15th in the sprint at [[Kontiolahti]], [[Finland]] in February [[2011\u201312 Biathlon World Cup|2012]].  She placed 17th in the individual race at the [[Biathlon World Championships 2011|2011 World Championships]] in [[Khanty-Mansiysk]], [[Russia]]. She was ranked 34th in the World Cup in the [[2010\u201311 Biathlon World Cup|2010\u201311]] season and 55th for [[2011\u201312 Biathlon World Cup|2011\u201312]].\n\nStudebaker, a member of the [[Biathlon at the 2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Winter Olympic]] team, placed 34th in the 15&nbsp;km individual at [[Whistler Olympic Park]], Canada.  She has been a member of the U.S. Biathlon Team since 2007, after her graduation from [[Dartmouth College]], where she captained the NCAA champion cross country ski team. Studebaker is a 2003 graduate of [[Boise High School]] and learned to ski at [[Bogus Basin]].\n\nStudebaker retired from the sport at the end of the 2013-14 season.<ref name=retirement>{{cite web |url=http://www5.biathlonworld.com/en/press_releases.html/do/detail?presse=2216 |title=Retiring from Biathlon; Part 2, the Women |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=29 April 2014 |website=[[International Biathlon Union]] |accessdate=23 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103161722/http://www5.biathlonworld.com/en/press_releases.html/do/detail?presse=2216 |archivedate=3 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 she married biathlete Zach Hall.\n\n==External links==\n*{{Blogspot|sarastudebaker|Official page}}\n*[http://www4.biathlonworld.com/en/athletes.html/do/showathlete?IBUId=BTUSA20710198401 IBU profile] \u2013 Sara Studebaker\n*[http://www.teamusa.org/Athletes/ST/Sara-Studebaker.aspx Team USA.org] \u2013 Sara Studebaker\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/st/sara-studebaker-1.html Sports-Reference.com] \u2013 Olympic results \u2013 Sara Studebaker\n*[http://www.boiseweekly.com/boise/who-sara-studebaker/Content?oid=2690143 Boise Weekly.com] \u2013 Sara Studebaker\n*[http://i.nbcolympics.com/athletes/athlete=2613/index.html NBC Olympics] \u2013 Sara Studebaker\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Studebaker, Sara}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American female biathletes]]\n[[Category:Biathletes at the 2010 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Biathletes at the 2014 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic biathletes of the United 