 |first=Irfan Ul |date=15 January 2019 |website=Images  |access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Zebaish]]'' \n|\n|Writer and actress\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Pakistani actresses]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* {{official website|http://bushraansari.com/}} \n* {{IMDb name|name=Bushra Ansari|id=2558798}}\n\n{{Pride of Performance for Arts}}\n{{Hum Awards hosts}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ansari, Bushra}}\n[[Category:Pakistani female singers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Pakistani television actresses]]\n[[Category:Pakistani television producers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Pakistani comedians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Pride of Performance]]\n[[Category:Lahore College for Women University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani voice actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Pakistani actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Pakistani actresses]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Women television producers]]\n[[Category:Muhajir people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Pakistani women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Pakistani women singers]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c5:8d8a:dd00:1822:de50:ce19:9d9b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bushra_Ansari"}
{"title_page": "James Murphy (electronic musician)", "text_new": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = James Murphy\n|background = solo_singer\n|image = James Murphy performing in 2016.jpg\n|image_size = 255px\n|caption = Murphy performing as part of [[LCD Soundsystem]] in June 2016.\n|birth_name = James Jeremiah Murphy\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1970|2|4}}\n|birth_place = [[Princeton Junction, New Jersey]], United States<ref>[http://www.fabriclondon.com/press/beta/archives/698-Biography-James-Murphy-Pat-Mahoney.html Biography: James Murphy & Pat Mahoney&nbsp;\u2013 Fabric London Press Website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071126064752/http://www.fabriclondon.com/press/beta/archives/698-Biography-James-Murphy-Pat-Mahoney.html |date=November 26, 2007 }}</ref>\n|genre = {{hlist|[[Dance-punk]]|[[electronica]]|[[post-punk revival]]|{{nowrap|[[alternative dance]]}}|[[indie rock]]}}\n|occupation = {{hlist|Musician|DJ|singer|songwriter|record producer}}\n|years_active = 1988\u2013present\n|label = [[DFA Records|DFA]]\n|associated_acts = {{hlist|[[LCD Soundsystem]]|[[Soulwax]]|Falling Man|Pony|Speedking|[[The Juan MacLean]]|[[Six Finger Satellite]]|[[The Rapture (band)|The Rapture]]|[[!!!]]|[[Out Hud]]|[[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]]|[[Pulp (band)|Pulp]]|[[Arcade Fire]]|[[David Bowie]]|[[Hot Chip]]|[[Gorillaz]]}}\n|website = {{unbulleted list|[http://www.dfarecords.com DFA Records]|[http://www.lcdsoundsystem.com LCD Soundsystem]}}\n|instruments = {{hlist|Vocals|bass guitar|drums|percussion|guitar|keyboards|piano}}\n}}\n\n'''James Jeremiah Murphy'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ascap.com/ace/#ace/writer/458340938/MURPHY%20JAMES%20JEREMIAH|title=ASCAP Ace Search|last=Murphy|first=James Jeremiah|publisher=[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] (ASCAP)|accessdate=May 17, 2017}}</ref> (born February 4, 1970) is an American musician, DJ, singer, songwriter, and record producer. His most well-known musical project is [[LCD Soundsystem]], which first gained attention with its single \"[[Losing My Edge]]\" in 2002 before releasing its [[LCD Soundsystem (album)|eponymous debut album]] in February 2005 to critical acclaim and top 20 success in the UK. LCD Soundsystem's second and third studio albums, ''[[Sound of Silver]]'' (2007) and ''[[This Is Happening]]'' (2010) respectively, were met with universal acclaim from several music review outlets.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14257-this-is-happening/|title = LCD Soundsystem Pitchfork Review|date = May 17, 2010|accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/this-is-happening-20100517|title = This Is Happening Rolling Stone Review|date = |accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/sound-of-silver-20070309|title = Sound of Silver Rolling Stone Review|date = |accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/10017-sound-of-silver/|title = Sound of Silver Pitchfork Review|date = |accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.metacritic.com/music/sound-of-silver/lcd-soundsystem|title = Sound of Silver Metacritic Review|date = |accessdate = |website = metacritic.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.metacritic.com/music/this-is-happening/lcd-soundsystem|title = This Is Happening Metacritic Review|date = |accessdate = |website = metacritic.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Both albums have also reached the top 50 in the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.billboard.com/artist/276744/lcd-soundsystem/chart|title = LCD Soundsystem Billboard listing|date = |accessdate = |website = billboard.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nLCD Soundsystem has been recognized as a major force in recent music and on March 5, 2013 was named one of ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\u2019s New Immortals\u2014\"currently active (or relatively recently defunct) artists who [they] think will stand the test of time.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-new-immortals-20130305|title = The New Immortals|date = March 5, 2013|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> In 2011, it was announced that LCD Soundsystem would disband with a final show on April 11, 2011 at Madison Square Garden. In the following years, Murphy continued to pursue other artistic projects: some music related, others not. In early 2016, the band announced a reunion as well as an appearance at the 2016 [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella Festival]], with their fourth album ''[[American Dream (LCD Soundsystem album)|American Dream]]'' and respective tour following afterwards in 2017.\nIn May 2018 LCD soundsystem were headliners at All Points East festival in Victoria Park London.\n\n==Early musical projects==\nMurphy was born and grew up in [[Princeton Junction, New Jersey]]<ref>[http://nymag.com/arts/popmusic/profiles/29425/ \"LCD Soundsystem's James Murphy on Bringing Back New York's Disco Days -- New York Magazine\"] \"Murphy grew up a suburban punk-rocker in Princeton Junction, New Jersey, where he stayed for a year after high school to train as a competitive kickboxer\".</ref> and graduated from [[West Windsor-Plainsboro High School South]] in 1988.<ref>Miller, Lynn. [https://communitynews.org/2006/12/15/where-have-you-gone-ww-p-class-of-1987/ \"Where Have You Gone, WW-P Class of 1987?\"], ''Community News'', December 15, 2006. Accessed January 26, 2020. \"Grammy-nominated James Murphy who records as 'LCD Soundsystem' is a classmate from the Class of 1988.\"</ref>\n\nHe has cited his influences as [[Liquid Liquid]], [[The B-52's|B52's]], [[Talking Heads]], [[The Fall (band)|The Fall]], [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[The Velvet Underground]], [[Yes (band)|Yes]], [[David Bowie]], [[Daft Punk]] and [[Can (band)|Can]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heyreverb.com/blog/2013/05/30/james-murphy-talks-influences-and-favorite-songs-releases-dj-set/69719/ |title=James Murphy talks influences and favorite songs, releases DJ set |website=Reverb |last=Owens |first=Dylan |date=30 May 2013 |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> Murphy was a member of Falling Man from 1988 to 1989, Pony from 1992 to 1994, and Speedking from 1995 to 1997. He was also the sound engineer for [[Sub Pop]] band [[Six Finger Satellite]]. (Former Six Finger Satellite member John Maclean is now on Murphy's record label as [[The Juan MacLean]].)\n\nMurphy attended [[New York University]], where he was an English major but later dropped out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/lectures/james-murphy |title=James Murphy |publisher=[[Red Bull Music Academy]] |date=2013 |accessdate=2016-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/05/10/lets-dance |title=Let's Dance |publisher=[[The New Yorker]] |first=Sasha |last=Frere-Jones |date=2010-05-10 |accessdate=2016-04-02}}</ref> At age 22, Murphy was offered a job writing for the sitcom ''[[Seinfeld]]'' which was then little-known. He did not expect the show to be successful and chose to continue with music instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/fridayreview/story/0,,1337870,00.html |title='I speak as a lifetime failure' &#124; &#124; Guardian Unlimited Arts |publisher=Arts.guardian.co.uk |date= |accessdate= |location=London}}</ref>\n\n=== DFA Records ===\nStarting in 1993, Murphy used the name Death from Above when DJing, a nickname that was given to his signature PA setup while he was the sound setup for [[Six Finger Satellite]]. Murphy engineered Northern Irish DJ [[David Holmes (musician)|David Holmes]]\u2019 album ''[[Bow Down to the Exit Sign]] ''and was introduced to the record\u2019s co-producer, [[Tim Goldsworthy]] (formerly of [[UNKLE]]).  Goldsworthy and Murphy would DJ together on the [[Lower East Side]], doing so with diverse genres of music.  They went on to found DFA Records with [[Jonathan Galkin]] in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/7947-you-were-there-the-complete-lcd-soundsystem/|title = You Were There: The Complete LCD Soundsystem|date = March 28, 2011|accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>  The name \"Death from Above\" led to a dispute with a two-man Canadian band also using the same name. In response to a legal threat, the Canadian group changed their name to [[Death from Above 1979]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6036-jukebox-james-murphy |title=Pitchfork Feature: Jukebox: James Murphy |publisher=Pitchfork.com |date=2005-05-09 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==LCD Soundsystem==\n{{Main|LCD Soundsystem}}\n\n=== ''LCD Soundsystem'' ===\nIn 2001 Murphy started the [[electronica|electronic]] [[dance-punk]] band [[LCD Soundsystem]]. The band first came to attention with its first single \"[[Losing My Edge]]\". The band released its [[LCD Soundsystem (album)|self-titled debut album]] in 2005 to critical acclaim.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n=== ''Sound of Silver'' ===\n[[File:Rock en Seine 2007, LCD Soundsystem 2.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Murphy at Route Du Rock in August 2007.]]\nMurphy's second LCD Soundsystem album, entitled ''[[Sound of Silver]]'', was released on March 12, 2007.<ref>[http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/40105/James_Murphy_Talks_Exercise_New_LP_Future_Plans James Murphy talks exercise, new LP, future plans] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006180704/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/40105/James_Murphy_Talks_Exercise_New_LP_Future_Plans |date=October 6, 2008 }}</ref> In its aftermath, he quipped to ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'': \"You don't have to work very hard to write an article about us. \"Just use the words 'unlikely frontman', 'bear-like', 'unshaven', '[[Talking Heads]]', blah blah blah...\"<ref>''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'', date unknown</ref>\n\nIn October 2009 [[Pitchfork Media]] named the track \"[[All My Friends (LCD Soundsystem song)|All My Friends]]\" off ''Sound of Silver'', the second best song of the decade, and a week later, Sound of Silver was ranked at #17 in The Top 200 Albums of the 2000s list. He also has a CD in the [[Fabric discography|Fabriclive CD series]], ''[[Fabric Live 36]]'', made in collaboration with LCD Soundsystem drummer Pat Mahoney, released in October 2007.<ref>[http://www.fabriclondon.com/label/release.php?item=fl36/jam FabricLive.36 James Murphy & Pat Mahoney]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210145437/http://www.fabriclondon.com/label/release.php?item=fl36%2Fjam |date=February 10, 2009 }}</ref> In late 2008 Murphy also announced he is to play [[bass guitar]] in [[Free Energy (band)|Free Energy]], a [[classic rock]] band, with LCD Soundsystem drummer Pat Mahoney and friends Scott Wells and Paul Sprangers,<ref>{{cite news|first=Sean|last=Michaels |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/oct/21/lcdsoundsystem-classic-rock-project |title=LCD Soundsystem announce 'classic rock' side project |publisher=Guardian |date= October 21, 2008|accessdate= |location=London}}</ref> although this was later refuted by Murphy as a misinterpretation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forums.dfarecords.co.uk/viewtopic.php?t=5035&postdays=0&postorder=asc&start=15 |title=DFA Board: LCD Soundsystem's James Murphy in new band |publisher=Forums.dfarecords.co.uk |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210060633/http://forums.dfarecords.co.uk/viewtopic.php?t=5035&postdays=0&postorder=asc&start=15 |archivedate=2009-02-10 }}</ref>\n\n=== ''This Is Happening'' and disbandment ===\n[[File:James Murphy 2010.jpg|250px|thumb|left|Murphy at Berlin Festival 2010.]]\nIn late 2009 Murphy moved into [[film score|film scoring]], writing music for [[Noah Baumbach]]'s film ''[[Greenberg (film)|Greenberg]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Adams |first=Sean |url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/4138468-lcd-soundsystem--10-questions-for-2010 |title=10 Questions: LCD Soundsystem |publisher=Drowned in Sound |date=2009-11-24 |accessdate=}}</ref> The [[Greenberg (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] was released on March 22, 2010. LCD Soundsystem's third album ''[[This Is Happening]]'' was released on May 17, 2010 in the UK and May 18 in the US. The album was recorded over the course of 2009 and early 2010 in [[The Mansion (recording studio)|the Mansion]]. April saw the release of the first single \"Drunk Girls\" with an accompanying music video directed by [[Spike Jonze]]. The album is dedicated to [[Jerry Fuchs]] (1974\u20132009), who had performed drums live with the band on occasion as well as having a big part with other associated DFA acts.\n\nMurphy announced his retirement from LCD Soundsystem with the release of ''This Is Happening'', and made his last television appearance under that name on February 14, 2011, on ''[[The Colbert Report]]''. His last concert at [[Madison Square Garden]] was simulcast streaming on [[Pitchfork Media]]'s website on April 2, 2011.\n\nIn July 2012, ''[[Shut Up and Play the Hits]]'', a documentary film about James Murphy and LCD Soundsystem's final concert, received a limited theatrical release in the US and subsequently in UK cinemas and on Blu-ray and DVD. The film follows James Murphy over a 48-hour period, from the day of the band's final gig at [[Madison Square Garden]] to the morning after the show.<ref name=\"huff\">{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/11/shut-up-and-play-the-hits-lcd-soundsystem-trailer_n_1200406.html | title='Shut Up And Play The Hits': LCD Soundsystem Film Trailer Released | publisher=Huffington Post | accessdate=January 12, 2012 | first=Gazelle | last=Emami | date=January 11, 2012}}</ref> The film also features intermittent segments from an extended interview between Murphy and pop culture writer [[Chuck Klosterman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/07/17/156725951/at-his-zenith-an-unlikely-rock-star-bows-out|title=At His Zenith, An Unlikely Rock Star Bows Out|first=Ian|last=Buckwalter|publisher=[[National Public Radio|NPR]]|accessdate=2012-07-27}}</ref>\n\n===Reunion and ''American Dream'' (2015\u2013present)===\nIn October 2015, over 5 years after the band's third and previously final album, ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' reported that \"multiple sources\" confirmed LCD Soundsystem's reunion in 2016 by headlining multiple \"high-profile music festivals in the US and UK\". The report was also confirmed by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' the same day, but quickly after these rumours, DFA Records label manager Kris Petersen denied the reunion of the band, with DFA co-founder Jonathan Galkin seconding the denial in a ''[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]'' article.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/60997-lcd-soundsystem-not-reuniting-despite-reports/|title=LCD Soundsystem not reuniting, despite reports|first=Amy|last=Phillips|publisher=Pitchfork|accessdate=2016-01-14}}</ref>\n\nHowever, on December 24, 2015, the band contradicted these denials by releasing a new single, \"[[Christmas Will Break Your Heart]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/62659-lcd-soundsystem-share-new-song-christmas-will-break-your-heart/|title=LCD Soundsystem share new song \"Christmas Will Break Your Heart\"|first=Matthew|last=Strauss|publisher=Pitchfork|accessdate=2016-01-14}}</ref> After the new single, on January 4, 2016, LCD Soundsystem confirmed that they would be headlining the 2016 [[Coachella Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/62459-coachella-2016-lineup-announced/|title=Coachella 2016 lineup announced|first=Evan|last=Minsker|publisher=Pitchfork|accessdate=2016-01-14}}</ref> The day following on January 5, 2016, Murphy confirmed [[American Dream (LCD Soundsystem album)|a new studio album]] in 2016 in addition to other unspecified appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/lcd-soundsystem--2/90610|title=LCD Soundsystem release comeback statement: 'We\u2019re not just touring. We\u2019re releasing a record'|first=James|last=Hendicott|publisher=NME|accessdate=2016-01-14}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2017, Murphy announced two new LCD Soundsystem singles entitled \"Call the Police\" and \"American Dream\" were to be released at midnight, coinciding with their performance on ''Saturday Night Live''. He also said that the album was nearing completion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/73282-lcd-soundsystem-relasing-2-new-songs-call-the-police-and-american-dream-today/|title=LCD Soundsystem Releasing 2 New Songs \"Call the Police\" and \"American Dream\"|first=Matthew|last=Strauss|publisher=Pitchfork|accessdate=2017-05-19}}</ref> ''American Dream'' was released on September 1, 2017 through DFA Records and Columbia Records.<ref name=\"cos AmDreamRelease\">{{Cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/06/lcd-soundsystem-announce-new-album-american-dream-plus-lengthy-tour/ |title=LCD Soundsystem announce new album American Dream, plus lengthy tour |last=Young |first=Alex |work=Consequence of Sound |publication-date=June 19, 2017 |accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other projects==\n[[File:James_Murphy_by_Sachyn_Mital.jpg|thumb|right|James Murphy DJing at the 2013 CBGB Festival.]]\nAfter the disbandment of LCD Soundsystem (between 2011 and 2015), James Murphy pursued other artistic projects including remixing, directing, developing his own espresso, producing, and putting out footage and audio from LCD Soundsystem's final show. Murphy has stated that dissolving LCD Soundsystem has made it possible for him to experiment with other projects. \"So [these projects] [become] possible, which is incredible. I get to do all this crazy shit \u2013 and if I ever wanted to be in a band again, I can probably figure that out.\" He has also stated how much time the creation of an album takes and that time can be spent doing other activities. \"I wouldn\u2019t have a record coming out in April if I had done all [these projects]. It\u2019s impossible. And if I had a record coming out in April, I would have been fucking invisible for two years.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> Though Murphy has illustrated a great freedom with his spare time after the band, he also \u201cmiss[es] it a lot [at times]\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/james-murphy-is-finally-a-free-man-20140603|title = James Murphy Is Finally a Free Man|date = June 3, 2014|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n=== Britney Spears ===\nIn 2003, Murphy worked with pop singer [[Britney Spears]] on her album ''[[In the Zone]]'', but the collaboration was unsuccessful. According to Murphy, \"She seemed eager to please, but it went nowhere. She went to dinner and just never came back.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/lcd-soundsystem-53-1345685|title=James Murphy recalls working with 'strange' Britney|last=NME|date=2007-03-21|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-30}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Reflektor'' ===\nMurphy worked on [[Arcade Fire]]'s fourth studio album ''[[Reflektor]].'' A [[Win Butler]] interview conducted by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' revealed that he thought of LCD Soundsystem \"like [[New Order (band)|New Order]] and the [[B-52's]]\". He continued to state that Arcade Fire are influenced by bands that have also influenced LCD Soundsystem. A collaboration between Arcade Fire and James Murphy has been intended since Arcade Fire's sophomore album ''[[Neon Bible]],'' however time conflicts prevented such a collaboration.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/win-butler-reveals-secret-influences-behind-arcade-fires-reflektor-20131022|title = Win Butler Reveals Secret Influences Behind Arcade Fire's 'Reflektor'|date = October 22, 2013|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Though Murphy has regularly stated in interviews that he \"didn't do that much\" to help Arcade Fire, he has said that he worked the most extensively on the song Awful Sound (Oh Eurydice).<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/james-murphy-on-little-duck-and-producing-arcade-fires-reflektor-20131104|title = James Murphy on 'Little Duck' and Producing Arcade Fire's 'Reflektor'|date = November 4, 2013|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Butler predicts that the band and James Murphy will collaborate again in the future, as he feels \"like [they] have more work to do\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Despacio ===\nTogether with David and Stephen Dewaele of 2ManyDjs and engineer John Klett, Murphy designed Despacio: a formation of eight McIntosh speakers stacked to eleven feet. The idea for the system came from Murphy and the Dewaele brother's dissatisfaction with the evolution of [[DJ]] culture and how DJing has become more of a \u201cshow-spectacle-type scenario\u201d and has departed from the days of people dancing in the dark with little attention to the DJ. The design is \u201cdesigned for really immersive listening\u201d. The reason behind creating and performing with Despacio is to encourage DJs to implement a similar sound system, altering the course of DJ culture to its dance roots.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/james-murphy-on-despacio-lcd-soundsystems-live-album-and-new-music-20131211|title = James Murphy on Despacio, LCD Soundsystem's Live Album and New Music|date = December 11, 2013|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n=== Subway Symphony ===\nJames Murphy has been attempting to change the sound of the New York [[turnstile]] beeps since 1999. Murphy has described the current turnstile sound as of 2014 as a \u201cdissonant rubbing-Styrofoam-on-glass squeak\u201d that is \u201chorrible\u201d. Because the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|Metropolitan Transit Authority]] plans to update the system by 2019, Murphy has proposed his turnstile plan that would have each turnstile harmonize with others by emitting three-to-five note sequences. Installing new sound chips will be an easier task during the renovations. Murphy feels that the more pleasant sounds will also help people's attitudes toward taking the subway. He believes that people will \"feel a nostalgia\" for certain destinations when hearing its unique melody.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/feb/25/lcd-soundsystem-james-murphy-soundtrack-new-york-subways|title = NYC Soundsystem: James Murphy in bid to create soundtrack for subways|date = February 25, 2014|accessdate = |website = theguardian.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Murphy is prepared for the responsibilities if the idea is green-lit by the MTA and would be \u201cbroken hearted [if it doesn\u2019t happen]\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/james-murphy-wants-to-make-nyc-subway-turnstiles-more-musical-20140224|title = James Murphy Wants to Make NYC Subway Turnstiles More Musical|date = February 24, 2014|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, he partnered with [[Heineken]] to launch the project, branded as the \u201cSubway Symphony.\u201d However, the MTA has denied any possibility of the project happening, as the standard turnstile beep is a necessary [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA]]-compliant tool for the visually impaired.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Even This Beer Company Can't Save James Murphy's Subway Dream|url = http://gothamist.com/2015/06/11/james_murphy_subway_symphony.php|website = Gothamist|accessdate = 2015-06-15|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150615195613/http://gothamist.com/2015/06/11/james_murphy_subway_symphony.php|archivedate = 2015-06-15}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014 US Open Remixes ===\nCollaborating with [[IBM]], James Murphy \u201cremixed\u201d the 2014 [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] matches. Murphy composed an [[algorithm]] that generated pieces from the sounds and occurrences, such as [[Fault (tennis)|fault]], [[Point (tennis)|point]] and [[Ace (tennis)|ace]] for example, of the actual matches. Murphy cut his favorite moments from the pieces and created 14 remixes from them. The remixes were created in real time during the matches on US Open's website. The pieces are titled by their match number and are viewable on the website with visual accompaniment denoting points scored. The website categorizes the pieces by men's\u2019 matches, women's\u2019 matches and Murphy's 14 remixes.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-james-murphys-us-open-remixes-20140909|title = Hear James Murphy's US Open Remixes|date = September 9, 2014|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n=== David Bowie ===\nOn November 5, 2013, [[Columbia Records]] released ''The Next Day Extra'', a three-disc expanded edition of David Bowie's album ''[[The Next Day]]''. On the expanded edition, Murphy remixed the track \"[[Love Is Lost]]\". The title of the remix is \u201cLove is Lost (Hello Steve Reich Remix)\".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/news/52598-listen-james-murphy-remixes-david-bowies-love-is-lost/|title = Listen: James Murphy Remixes David Bowie's \"Love Is Lost\"|date = October 10, 2013|accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> When Murphy was offered to remix the track, he had not remixed a song in five years, making it \u201creally scary\u201d. He said \u201cit would have been scary if it was a remix for somebody I had never even heard of, but it was super scary to do that ''[Laughs]\u201d''.  David Bowie is a significant influence on Murphy's music.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\"/>\n\nMurphy was to be a producer for Bowie's final studio album, ''[[Blackstar (album)|Blackstar]]'', but it reportedly fell through. However, he does make a guest appearance on the album as a percussionist.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.factmag.com/2015/11/23/david-bowie-blackstar-james-murphy/ |title=David Bowie\u2019s Blackstar \"avoids rock & roll,\" features James Murphy |publisher=FactMag |date=2015-11-23 |accessdate=2015-11-27 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n=== \"Little Duck\" ===\nMurphy participated in [[Canon (photography)|Canon]]\u2019s Project Imaginat10n, which called for 5 celebrities to direct short films based on pictures uploaded by people around the world to the Project Imaginat10n site. The result was \u201cLittle Duck\u201d, Murphy's first directorial effort. [[Ron Howard]] advised Murphy in his directing.  Shooting took place in Japan, the setting of the film.  The film follows a young man who travels from Manhattan to Japan in order to help solve his brothers\u2019 problems.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/news/51820-watch-behind-the-scenes-of-james-murphys-short-film-little-duck/|title = Watch: Behind the Scenes of James Murphy's Short Film Little Duck|date = August 7, 2013|accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n=== House of Good ===\nIn collaboration with coffee company [[Blue Bottle Coffee Company|Blue Bottle]], Murphy created his signature coffee called House of Good.  It is described as a \u201csyrupy, well-balanced and thoroughly accessible\" espresso.  It was developed with help of Blue Bottle founder James Freeman.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/news/54121-james-murphys-signature-coffee-is-now-available/|title = James Murphy's Signature Coffee is Now Available|date = February 25, 2014|accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Shut Up and Play the Hits ''and ''The Long Goodbye'' ===\nLCD Soundsystem played their last show on April 11, 2011 at [[Madison Square Garden]].  Both a documentary and a complete recording of the show were made''. [[Shut Up and Play the Hits]]'', directed by Will Lovelace and Dylan Southern, documents the highlights of the show and Murphy's actions after it.  11 cinematographers captured the entire near four-hour show from different angles in addition to three roof cameras.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/apr/14/lcd-soundsystem-film|title = Shut Up And Play The Hits: the men behind the LCD Soundsystem movie|date = April 13, 2012|accessdate = |website = theguardian.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>  The documentary screened at select theaters around America for a limited time in 2012 and was later released in a DVD and Blu-ray form by Oscilloscope on October 9, 2012.  The physical form consisted of three discs that contained the documentary and footage of the entire concert.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/news/47439-lcd-soundsystem-film-shut-up-and-play-the-hits-gets-dvdblu-ray-release-date/|title = LCD Soundsystem Film Shut Up and Play the Hits Gets DVD/Blu-ray Release Date|date = August 8, 2012|accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n''[[The Long Goodbye: LCD Soundsystem Live at Madison Square Garden|The Long Goodbye]]'' is an audio capture of LCD Soundsystem's last show at Madison Square Garden.  James Murphy [[Mix (music)|mixed]] the audio, which was different from its video counterpart \u201cbecause the film is mixed for your eye and the record is mixed for your ears.\u201d  Murphy has stated that the work into mixing the audio has been strenuous and \u201cjust murder\u201d.  ''The Long Goodbye ''was released as a vinyl box set on [[Record Store Day|record store day]], April 19, 2014.  It was later released on vinyl and digitally.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\"/>    ''  ''\n\n=== Other projects ===\nHe recorded a song with [[Gorillaz]] and [[Outkast|OutKast]]'s [[Andre 3000]], called \"[[DoYaThing]]\", for their [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]] collection. It was released on February 23, 2012.{{cn|date=January 2020}} He produced a song with [[Pulp (band)|Pulp]] called \"[[After You (Pulp song)|After You]]\". It was released as a present on Christmas Day 2012 to fans.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/49006-listen-pulp-team-up-with-lcd-soundsystems-james-murphy-for-new-recording-after-you/|title=Listen: Pulp Team Up With LCD Soundsystem's James Murphy for New Recording \"After You\"|publisher=Pitchfork |date=2012-12-26 |accessdate= |location=New York}}</ref> Murphy also appeared in ''[[The Comedy (film)|The Comedy]]'' with [[Tim Heidecker]] and [[Eric Wareheim]].\n\nMurphy was listed as a producer for [[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]]' 2013 album, ''[[Mosquito (Yeah Yeah Yeahs album)|Mosquito]]''. He also wrote the musical scores for the [[Noah Baumbach]] films ''[[Greenberg (film)|Greenberg]]'' and ''[[While We're Young (film)|While We're Young]]''.\n\n=== Four Horsemen ===\nMurphy opened a wine bar named Four Horsemen in June 2015 in Williamsburg, Brooklyn, selling a range of natural red, white and orange wines.\n\n==Discography==\n\n=== With LCD Soundsystem ===\n{{Main|LCD Soundsystem discography}}\n* ''[[LCD Soundsystem (album)|LCD Soundsystem]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Sound of Silver]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[This Is Happening]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[American Dream (LCD Soundsystem album)|American Dream]]'' (2017)\n\n=== With Falling Man ===\n* ''A Christening'' (1988)\n\n=== With Pony ===\n* ''Cosmovalidator'' (1994)\n\n=== With Speedking ===\n* ''The Fist and the Laurels'' (2002)\n\n=== Solo ===\n* ''Remixes Made with Tennis Data'' (2014)\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|James Murphy (electronic musician)}}\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.npr.org/2010/06/21/127745800/james-murphy-the-man-behind-lcd-soundsystem In-depth radio interview] with James Murphy on ''[[Fresh Air]]'' (38 mins; 2010)\n\n{{LCD Soundsystem}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murphy, James}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American DJs]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Remixers]]\n[[Category:LCD Soundsystem members]]\n[[Category:Singers from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from West Windsor Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:West Windsor-Plainsboro High School South alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = James Murphy\n|background = solo_singer\n|image = James Murphy performing in 2016.jpg\n|image_size = 255px\n|caption = Murphy performing as part of [[LCD Soundsystem]] in June 2016.\n|birth_name = James Jeremiah Murphy\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1970|2|4}}\n|birth_place = [[Princeton Junction, New Jersey]], United States<ref>[http://www.fabriclondon.com/press/beta/archives/698-Biography-James-Murphy-Pat-Mahoney.html Biography: James Murphy & Pat Mahoney&nbsp;\u2013 Fabric London Press Website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071126064752/http://www.fabriclondon.com/press/beta/archives/698-Biography-James-Murphy-Pat-Mahoney.html |date=November 26, 2007 }}</ref>\n|genre = {{hlist|[[Dance-punk]]|[[electronica]]|[[post-punk revival]]|{{nowrap|[[alternative dance]]}}|[[indie rock]]}}\n|occupation = {{hlist|Musician|DJ|singer|songwriter|record producer}}\n|years_active = 1988\u2013present\n|label = [[DFA Records|DFA]]\n|associated_acts = {{hlist|[[LCD Soundsystem]]|[[Soulwax]]|Falling Man|Pony|Speedking|[[The Juan MacLean]]|[[Six Finger Satellite]]|[[The Rapture (band)|The Rapture]]|[[!!!]]|[[Out Hud]]|[[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]]|[[Pulp (band)|Pulp]]|[[Arcade Fire]]|[[David Bowie]]|[[Hot Chip]]|[[Gorillaz]]}}\n|website = {{unbulleted list|[http://www.dfarecords.com DFA Records]|[http://www.lcdsoundsystem.com LCD Soundsystem]}}\n|instruments = {{hlist|Vocals|bass guitar|drums|percussion|guitar|keyboards|piano}}\n}}\n\n'''James Jeremiah Murphy'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ascap.com/ace/#ace/writer/458340938/MURPHY%20JAMES%20JEREMIAH|title=ASCAP Ace Search|last=Murphy|first=James Jeremiah|publisher=[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] (ASCAP)|accessdate=May 17, 2017}}</ref> (born February 4, 1970) is an American musician, DJ, singer, songwriter, and record producer. His most well-known musical project is [[LCD Soundsystem]], which first gained attention with its single \"[[Losing My Edge]]\" in 2002 before releasing its [[LCD Soundsystem (album)|eponymous debut album]] in February 2005 to critical acclaim and top 20 success in the UK. LCD Soundsystem's second and third studio albums, ''[[Sound of Silver]]'' (2007) and ''[[This Is Happening]]'' (2010) respectively, were met with universal acclaim from several music review outlets.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14257-this-is-happening/|title = LCD Soundsystem Pitchfork Review|date = May 17, 2010|accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/this-is-happening-20100517|title = This Is Happening Rolling Stone Review|date = |accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/sound-of-silver-20070309|title = Sound of Silver Rolling Stone Review|date = |accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/10017-sound-of-silver/|title = Sound of Silver Pitchfork Review|date = |accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.metacritic.com/music/sound-of-silver/lcd-soundsystem|title = Sound of Silver Metacritic Review|date = |accessdate = |website = metacritic.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.metacritic.com/music/this-is-happening/lcd-soundsystem|title = This Is Happening Metacritic Review|date = |accessdate = |website = metacritic.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Both albums have also reached the top 50 in the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.billboard.com/artist/276744/lcd-soundsystem/chart|title = LCD Soundsystem Billboard listing|date = |accessdate = |website = billboard.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nLCD Soundsystem has been recognized as a major force in recent music and on March 5, 2013 was named one of ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\u2019s New Immortals - \"currently active (or relatively recently defunct) artists who [they] think will stand the test of time.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-new-immortals-20130305|title = The New Immortals|date = March 5, 2013|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> In 2011, it was announced that LCD Soundsystem would disband with a final show on April 11, 2011 at Madison Square Garden. In the following years, Murphy continued to pursue other artistic projects: some music related, others not. In early 2016, the band announced a reunion as well as an appearance at the 2016 [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella Festival]], with their fourth album ''[[American Dream (LCD Soundsystem album)|American Dream]]'' and respective tour following afterwards in 2017.\nIn May 2018 LCD soundsystem were headliners at All Points East festival in Victoria Park London.\n\n==Early musical projects==\nMurphy was born and grew up in [[Princeton Junction, New Jersey]]<ref>[http://nymag.com/arts/popmusic/profiles/29425/ \"LCD Soundsystem's James Murphy on Bringing Back New York's Disco Days -- New York Magazine\"] \"Murphy grew up a suburban punk-rocker in Princeton Junction, New Jersey, where he stayed for a year after high school to train as a competitive kickboxer\".</ref> and graduated from [[West Windsor-Plainsboro High School South]] in 1988.<ref>Miller, Lynn. [https://communitynews.org/2006/12/15/where-have-you-gone-ww-p-class-of-1987/ \"Where Have You Gone, WW-P Class of 1987?\"], ''Community News'', December 15, 2006. Accessed January 26, 2020. \"Grammy-nominated James Murphy who records as 'LCD Soundsystem' is a classmate from the Class of 1988.\"</ref>\n\nHe has cited his influences as [[Liquid Liquid]], [[The B-52's|B52's]], [[Talking Heads]], [[The Fall (band)|The Fall]], [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[The Velvet Underground]], [[Yes (band)|Yes]], [[David Bowie]], [[Daft Punk]] and [[Can (band)|Can]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heyreverb.com/blog/2013/05/30/james-murphy-talks-influences-and-favorite-songs-releases-dj-set/69719/ |title=James Murphy talks influences and favorite songs, releases DJ set |website=Reverb |last=Owens |first=Dylan |date=30 May 2013 |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> Murphy was a member of Falling Man from 1988 to 1989, Pony from 1992 to 1994, and Speedking from 1995 to 1997. He was also the sound engineer for [[Sub Pop]] band [[Six Finger Satellite]]. (Former Six Finger Satellite member John Maclean is now on Murphy's record label as [[The Juan MacLean]].)\n\nMurphy attended [[New York University]], where he was an English major but later dropped out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/lectures/james-murphy |title=James Murphy |publisher=[[Red Bull Music Academy]] |date=2013 |accessdate=2016-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/05/10/lets-dance |title=Let's Dance |publisher=[[The New Yorker]] |first=Sasha |last=Frere-Jones |date=2010-05-10 |accessdate=2016-04-02}}</ref> At age 22, Murphy was offered a job writing for the sitcom ''[[Seinfeld]]'' which was then little-known. He did not expect the show to be successful and chose to continue with music instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/fridayreview/story/0,,1337870,00.html |title='I speak as a lifetime failure' &#124; &#124; Guardian Unlimited Arts |publisher=Arts.guardian.co.uk |date= |accessdate= |location=London}}</ref>\n\n=== DFA Records ===\nStarting in 1993, Murphy used the name Death from Above when DJing, a nickname that was given to his signature PA setup while he was the sound setup for [[Six Finger Satellite]]. Murphy engineered Northern Irish DJ [[David Holmes (musician)|David Holmes]]\u2019 album ''[[Bow Down to the Exit Sign]] ''and was introduced to the record\u2019s co-producer, [[Tim Goldsworthy]] (formerly of [[UNKLE]]).  Goldsworthy and Murphy would DJ together on the [[Lower East Side]], doing so with diverse genres of music.  They went on to found DFA Records with [[Jonathan Galkin]] in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/7947-you-were-there-the-complete-lcd-soundsystem/|title = You Were There: The Complete LCD Soundsystem|date = March 28, 2011|accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>  The name \"Death from Above\" led to a dispute with a two-man Canadian band also using the same name. In response to a legal threat, the Canadian group changed their name to [[Death from Above 1979]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6036-jukebox-james-murphy |title=Pitchfork Feature: Jukebox: James Murphy |publisher=Pitchfork.com |date=2005-05-09 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==LCD Soundsystem==\n{{Main|LCD Soundsystem}}\n\n=== ''LCD Soundsystem'' ===\nIn 2001 Murphy started the [[electronica|electronic]] [[dance-punk]] band [[LCD Soundsystem]]. The band first came to attention with its first single \"[[Losing My Edge]]\". The band released its [[LCD Soundsystem (album)|self-titled debut album]] in 2005 to critical acclaim.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n=== ''Sound of Silver'' ===\n[[File:Rock en Seine 2007, LCD Soundsystem 2.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Murphy at Route Du Rock in August 2007.]]\nMurphy's second LCD Soundsystem album, entitled ''[[Sound of Silver]]'', was released on March 12, 2007.<ref>[http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/40105/James_Murphy_Talks_Exercise_New_LP_Future_Plans James Murphy talks exercise, new LP, future plans] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006180704/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/40105/James_Murphy_Talks_Exercise_New_LP_Future_Plans |date=October 6, 2008 }}</ref> In its aftermath, he quipped to ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'': \"You don't have to work very hard to write an article about us. \"Just use the words 'unlikely frontman', 'bear-like', 'unshaven', '[[Talking Heads]]', blah blah blah...\"<ref>''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'', date unknown</ref>\n\nIn October 2009 [[Pitchfork Media]] named the track \"[[All My Friends (LCD Soundsystem song)|All My Friends]]\" off ''Sound of Silver'', the second best song of the decade, and a week later, Sound of Silver was ranked at #17 in The Top 200 Albums of the 2000s list. He also has a CD in the [[Fabric discography|Fabriclive CD series]], ''[[Fabric Live 36]]'', made in collaboration with LCD Soundsystem drummer Pat Mahoney, released in October 2007.<ref>[http://www.fabriclondon.com/label/release.php?item=fl36/jam FabricLive.36 James Murphy & Pat Mahoney]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210145437/http://www.fabriclondon.com/label/release.php?item=fl36%2Fjam |date=February 10, 2009 }}</ref> In late 2008 Murphy also announced he is to play [[bass guitar]] in [[Free Energy (band)|Free Energy]], a [[classic rock]] band, with LCD Soundsystem drummer Pat Mahoney and friends Scott Wells and Paul Sprangers,<ref>{{cite news|first=Sean|last=Michaels |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/oct/21/lcdsoundsystem-classic-rock-project |title=LCD Soundsystem announce 'classic rock' side project |publisher=Guardian |date= October 21, 2008|accessdate= |location=London}}</ref> although this was later refuted by Murphy as a misinterpretation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forums.dfarecords.co.uk/viewtopic.php?t=5035&postdays=0&postorder=asc&start=15 |title=DFA Board: LCD Soundsystem's James Murphy in new band |publisher=Forums.dfarecords.co.uk |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210060633/http://forums.dfarecords.co.uk/viewtopic.php?t=5035&postdays=0&postorder=asc&start=15 |archivedate=2009-02-10 }}</ref>\n\n=== ''This Is Happening'' and disbandment ===\n[[File:James Murphy 2010.jpg|250px|thumb|left|Murphy at Berlin Festival 2010.]]\nIn late 2009 Murphy moved into [[film score|film scoring]], writing music for [[Noah Baumbach]]'s film ''[[Greenberg (film)|Greenberg]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Adams |first=Sean |url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/4138468-lcd-soundsystem--10-questions-for-2010 |title=10 Questions: LCD Soundsystem |publisher=Drowned in Sound |date=2009-11-24 |accessdate=}}</ref> The [[Greenberg (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] was released on March 22, 2010. LCD Soundsystem's third album ''[[This Is Happening]]'' was released on May 17, 2010 in the UK and May 18 in the US. The album was recorded over the course of 2009 and early 2010 in [[The Mansion (recording studio)|the Mansion]]. April saw the release of the first single \"Drunk Girls\" with an accompanying music video directed by [[Spike Jonze]]. The album is dedicated to [[Jerry Fuchs]] (1974\u20132009), who had performed drums live with the band on occasion as well as having a big part with other associated DFA acts.\n\nMurphy announced his retirement from LCD Soundsystem with the release of ''This Is Happening'', and made his last television appearance under that name on February 14, 2011, on ''[[The Colbert Report]]''. His last concert at [[Madison Square Garden]] was simulcast streaming on [[Pitchfork Media]]'s website on April 2, 2011.\n\nIn July 2012, ''[[Shut Up and Play the Hits]]'', a documentary film about James Murphy and LCD Soundsystem's final concert, received a limited theatrical release in the US and subsequently in UK cinemas and on Blu-ray and DVD. The film follows James Murphy over a 48-hour period, from the day of the band's final gig at [[Madison Square Garden]] to the morning after the show.<ref name=\"huff\">{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/11/shut-up-and-play-the-hits-lcd-soundsystem-trailer_n_1200406.html | title='Shut Up And Play The Hits': LCD Soundsystem Film Trailer Released | publisher=Huffington Post | accessdate=January 12, 2012 | first=Gazelle | last=Emami | date=January 11, 2012}}</ref> The film also features intermittent segments from an extended interview between Murphy and pop culture writer [[Chuck Klosterman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/07/17/156725951/at-his-zenith-an-unlikely-rock-star-bows-out|title=At His Zenith, An Unlikely Rock Star Bows Out|first=Ian|last=Buckwalter|publisher=[[National Public Radio|NPR]]|accessdate=2012-07-27}}</ref>\n\n===Reunion and ''American Dream'' (2015\u2013present)===\nIn October 2015, over 5 years after the band's third and previously final album, ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' reported that \"multiple sources\" confirmed LCD Soundsystem's reunion in 2016 by headlining multiple \"high-profile music festivals in the US and UK\". The report was also confirmed by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' the same day, but quickly after these rumours, DFA Records label manager Kris Petersen denied the reunion of the band, with DFA co-founder Jonathan Galkin seconding the denial in a ''[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]'' article.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/60997-lcd-soundsystem-not-reuniting-despite-reports/|title=LCD Soundsystem not reuniting, despite reports|first=Amy|last=Phillips|publisher=Pitchfork|accessdate=2016-01-14}}</ref>\n\nHowever, on December 24, 2015, the band contradicted these denials by releasing a new single, \"[[Christmas Will Break Your Heart]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/62659-lcd-soundsystem-share-new-song-christmas-will-break-your-heart/|title=LCD Soundsystem share new song \"Christmas Will Break Your Heart\"|first=Matthew|last=Strauss|publisher=Pitchfork|accessdate=2016-01-14}}</ref> After the new single, on January 4, 2016, LCD Soundsystem confirmed that they would be headlining the 2016 [[Coachella Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/62459-coachella-2016-lineup-announced/|title=Coachella 2016 lineup announced|first=Evan|last=Minsker|publisher=Pitchfork|accessdate=2016-01-14}}</ref> The day following on January 5, 2016, Murphy confirmed [[American Dream (LCD Soundsystem album)|a new studio album]] in 2016 in addition to other unspecified appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/lcd-soundsystem--2/90610|title=LCD Soundsystem release comeback statement: 'We\u2019re not just touring. We\u2019re releasing a record'|first=James|last=Hendicott|publisher=NME|accessdate=2016-01-14}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2017, Murphy announced two new LCD Soundsystem singles entitled \"Call the Police\" and \"American Dream\" were to be released at midnight, coinciding with their performance on ''Saturday Night Live''. He also said that the album was nearing completion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/73282-lcd-soundsystem-relasing-2-new-songs-call-the-police-and-american-dream-today/|title=LCD Soundsystem Releasing 2 New Songs \"Call the Police\" and \"American Dream\"|first=Matthew|last=Strauss|publisher=Pitchfork|accessdate=2017-05-19}}</ref> ''American Dream'' was released on September 1, 2017 through DFA Records and Columbia Records.<ref name=\"cos AmDreamRelease\">{{Cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/06/lcd-soundsystem-announce-new-album-american-dream-plus-lengthy-tour/ |title=LCD Soundsystem announce new album American Dream, plus lengthy tour |last=Young |first=Alex |work=Consequence of Sound |publication-date=June 19, 2017 |accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other projects==\n[[File:James_Murphy_by_Sachyn_Mital.jpg|thumb|right|James Murphy DJing at the 2013 CBGB Festival.]]\nAfter the disbandment of LCD Soundsystem (between 2011 and 2015), James Murphy pursued other artistic projects including remixing, directing, developing his own espresso, producing, and putting out footage and audio from LCD Soundsystem's final show. Murphy has stated that dissolving LCD Soundsystem has made it possible for him to experiment with other projects. \"So [these projects] [become] possible, which is incredible. I get to do all this crazy shit \u2013 and if I ever wanted to be in a band again, I can probably figure that out.\" He has also stated how much time the creation of an album takes and that time can be spent doing other activities. \"I wouldn\u2019t have a record coming out in April if I had done all [these projects]. It\u2019s impossible. And if I had a record coming out in April, I would have been fucking invisible for two years.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> Though Murphy has illustrated a great freedom with his spare time after the band, he also \u201cmiss[es] it a lot [at times]\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/james-murphy-is-finally-a-free-man-20140603|title = James Murphy Is Finally a Free Man|date = June 3, 2014|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n=== Britney Spears ===\nIn 2003, Murphy worked with pop singer [[Britney Spears]] on her album ''[[In the Zone]]'', but the collaboration was unsuccessful. According to Murphy, \"She seemed eager to please, but it went nowhere. She went to dinner and just never came back.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/lcd-soundsystem-53-1345685|title=James Murphy recalls working with 'strange' Britney|last=NME|date=2007-03-21|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-30}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Reflektor'' ===\nMurphy worked on [[Arcade Fire]]'s fourth studio album ''[[Reflektor]].'' A [[Win Butler]] interview conducted by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' revealed that he thought of LCD Soundsystem \"like [[New Order (band)|New Order]] and the [[B-52's]]\". He continued to state that Arcade Fire are influenced by bands that have also influenced LCD Soundsystem. A collaboration between Arcade Fire and James Murphy has been intended since Arcade Fire's sophomore album ''[[Neon Bible]],'' however time conflicts prevented such a collaboration.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/win-butler-reveals-secret-influences-behind-arcade-fires-reflektor-20131022|title = Win Butler Reveals Secret Influences Behind Arcade Fire's 'Reflektor'|date = October 22, 2013|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Though Murphy has regularly stated in interviews that he \"didn't do that much\" to help Arcade Fire, he has said that he worked the most extensively on the song Awful Sound (Oh Eurydice).<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/james-murphy-on-little-duck-and-producing-arcade-fires-reflektor-20131104|title = James Murphy on 'Little Duck' and Producing Arcade Fire's 'Reflektor'|date = November 4, 2013|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Butler predicts that the band and James Murphy will collaborate again in the future, as he feels \"like [they] have more work to do\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Despacio ===\nTogether with David and Stephen Dewaele of 2ManyDjs and engineer John Klett, Murphy designed Despacio: a formation of eight McIntosh speakers stacked to eleven feet. The idea for the system came from Murphy and the Dewaele brother's dissatisfaction with the evolution of [[DJ]] culture and how DJing has become more of a \u201cshow-spectacle-type scenario\u201d and has departed from the days of people dancing in the dark with little attention to the DJ. The design is \u201cdesigned for really immersive listening\u201d. The reason behind creating and performing with Despacio is to encourage DJs to implement a similar sound system, altering the course of DJ culture to its dance roots.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/james-murphy-on-despacio-lcd-soundsystems-live-album-and-new-music-20131211|title = James Murphy on Despacio, LCD Soundsystem's Live Album and New Music|date = December 11, 2013|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n=== Subway Symphony ===\nJames Murphy has been attempting to change the sound of the New York [[turnstile]] beeps since 1999. Murphy has described the current turnstile sound as of 2014 as a \u201cdissonant rubbing-Styrofoam-on-glass squeak\u201d that is \u201chorrible\u201d. Because the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|Metropolitan Transit Authority]] plans to update the system by 2019, Murphy has proposed his turnstile plan that would have each turnstile harmonize with others by emitting three-to-five note sequences. Installing new sound chips will be an easier task during the renovations. Murphy feels that the more pleasant sounds will also help people's attitudes toward taking the subway. He believes that people will \"feel a nostalgia\" for certain destinations when hearing its unique melody.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/feb/25/lcd-soundsystem-james-murphy-soundtrack-new-york-subways|title = NYC Soundsystem: James Murphy in bid to create soundtrack for subways|date = February 25, 2014|accessdate = |website = theguardian.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Murphy is prepared for the responsibilities if the idea is green-lit by the MTA and would be \u201cbroken hearted [if it doesn\u2019t happen]\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/james-murphy-wants-to-make-nyc-subway-turnstiles-more-musical-20140224|title = James Murphy Wants to Make NYC Subway Turnstiles More Musical|date = February 24, 2014|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, he partnered with [[Heineken]] to launch the project, branded as the \u201cSubway Symphony.\u201d However, the MTA has denied any possibility of the project happening, as the standard turnstile beep is a necessary [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA]]-compliant tool for the visually impaired.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Even This Beer Company Can't Save James Murphy's Subway Dream|url = http://gothamist.com/2015/06/11/james_murphy_subway_symphony.php|website = Gothamist|accessdate = 2015-06-15|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150615195613/http://gothamist.com/2015/06/11/james_murphy_subway_symphony.php|archivedate = 2015-06-15}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014 US Open Remixes ===\nCollaborating with [[IBM]], James Murphy \u201cremixed\u201d the 2014 [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] matches. Murphy composed an [[algorithm]] that generated pieces from the sounds and occurrences, such as [[Fault (tennis)|fault]], [[Point (tennis)|point]] and [[Ace (tennis)|ace]] for example, of the actual matches. Murphy cut his favorite moments from the pieces and created 14 remixes from them. The remixes were created in real time during the matches on US Open's website. The pieces are titled by their match number and are viewable on the website with visual accompaniment denoting points scored. The website categorizes the pieces by men's\u2019 matches, women's\u2019 matches and Murphy's 14 remixes.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-james-murphys-us-open-remixes-20140909|title = Hear James Murphy's US Open Remixes|date = September 9, 2014|accessdate = |website = rollingstone.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n=== David Bowie ===\nOn November 5, 2013, [[Columbia Records]] released ''The Next Day Extra'', a three-disc expanded edition of David Bowie's album ''[[The Next Day]]''. On the expanded edition, Murphy remixed the track \"[[Love Is Lost]]\". The title of the remix is \u201cLove is Lost (Hello Steve Reich Remix)\".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/news/52598-listen-james-murphy-remixes-david-bowies-love-is-lost/|title = Listen: James Murphy Remixes David Bowie's \"Love Is Lost\"|date = October 10, 2013|accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> When Murphy was offered to remix the track, he had not remixed a song in five years, making it \u201creally scary\u201d. He said \u201cit would have been scary if it was a remix for somebody I had never even heard of, but it was super scary to do that ''[Laughs]\u201d''.  David Bowie is a significant influence on Murphy's music.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\"/>\n\nMurphy was to be a producer for Bowie's final studio album, ''[[Blackstar (album)|Blackstar]]'', but it reportedly fell through. However, he does make a guest appearance on the album as a percussionist.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.factmag.com/2015/11/23/david-bowie-blackstar-james-murphy/ |title=David Bowie\u2019s Blackstar \"avoids rock & roll,\" features James Murphy |publisher=FactMag |date=2015-11-23 |accessdate=2015-11-27 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n=== \"Little Duck\" ===\nMurphy participated in [[Canon (photography)|Canon]]\u2019s Project Imaginat10n, which called for 5 celebrities to direct short films based on pictures uploaded by people around the world to the Project Imaginat10n site. The result was \u201cLittle Duck\u201d, Murphy's first directorial effort. [[Ron Howard]] advised Murphy in his directing.  Shooting took place in Japan, the setting of the film.  The film follows a young man who travels from Manhattan to Japan in order to help solve his brothers\u2019 problems.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/news/51820-watch-behind-the-scenes-of-james-murphys-short-film-little-duck/|title = Watch: Behind the Scenes of James Murphy's Short Film Little Duck|date = August 7, 2013|accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n=== House of Good ===\nIn collaboration with coffee company [[Blue Bottle Coffee Company|Blue Bottle]], Murphy created his signature coffee called House of Good.  It is described as a \u201csyrupy, well-balanced and thoroughly accessible\" espresso.  It was developed with help of Blue Bottle founder James Freeman.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/news/54121-james-murphys-signature-coffee-is-now-available/|title = James Murphy's Signature Coffee is Now Available|date = February 25, 2014|accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Shut Up and Play the Hits ''and ''The Long Goodbye'' ===\nLCD Soundsystem played their last show on April 11, 2011 at [[Madison Square Garden]].  Both a documentary and a complete recording of the show were made''. [[Shut Up and Play the Hits]]'', directed by Will Lovelace and Dylan Southern, documents the highlights of the show and Murphy's actions after it.  11 cinematographers captured the entire near four-hour show from different angles in addition to three roof cameras.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/apr/14/lcd-soundsystem-film|title = Shut Up And Play The Hits: the men behind the LCD Soundsystem movie|date = April 13, 2012|accessdate = |website = theguardian.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>  The documentary screened at select theaters around America for a limited time in 2012 and was later released in a DVD and Blu-ray form by Oscilloscope on October 9, 2012.  The physical form consisted of three discs that contained the documentary and footage of the entire concert.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/news/47439-lcd-soundsystem-film-shut-up-and-play-the-hits-gets-dvdblu-ray-release-date/|title = LCD Soundsystem Film Shut Up and Play the Hits Gets DVD/Blu-ray Release Date|date = August 8, 2012|accessdate = |website = pitchfork.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n''[[The Long Goodbye: LCD Soundsystem Live at Madison Square Garden|The Long Goodbye]]'' is an audio capture of LCD Soundsystem's last show at Madison Square Garden.  James Murphy [[Mix (music)|mixed]] the audio, which was different from its video counterpart \u201cbecause the film is mixed for your eye and the record is mixed for your ears.\u201d  Murphy has stated that the work into mixing the audio has been strenuous and \u201cjust murder\u201d.  ''The Long Goodbye ''was released as a vinyl box set on [[Record Store Day|record store day]], April 19, 2014.  It was later released on vinyl and digitally.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\"/>    ''  ''\n\n=== Other projects ===\nHe recorded a song with [[Gorillaz]] and [[Outkast|OutKast]]'s [[Andre 3000]], called \"[[DoYaThing]]\", for their [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]] collection. It was released on February 23, 2012.{{cn|date=January 2020}} He produced a song with [[Pulp (band)|Pulp]] called \"[[After You (Pulp song)|After You]]\". It was released as a present on Christmas Day 2012 to fans.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/49006-listen-pulp-team-up-with-lcd-soundsystems-james-murphy-for-new-recording-after-you/|title=Listen: Pulp Team Up With LCD Soundsystem's James Murphy for New Recording \"After You\"|publisher=Pitchfork |date=2012-12-26 |accessdate= |location=New York}}</ref> Murphy also appeared in ''[[The Comedy (film)|The Comedy]]'' with [[Tim Heidecker]] and [[Eric Wareheim]].\n\nMurphy was listed as a producer for [[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]]' 2013 album, ''[[Mosquito (Yeah Yeah Yeahs album)|Mosquito]]''. He also wrote the musical scores for the [[Noah Baumbach]] films ''[[Greenberg (film)|Greenberg]]'' and ''[[While We're Young (film)|While We're Young]]''.\n\n=== Four Horsemen ===\nMurphy opened a wine bar named Four Horsemen in June 2015 in Williamsburg, Brooklyn, selling a range of natural red, white and orange wines.\n\n==Discography==\n\n=== With LCD Soundsystem ===\n{{Main|LCD Soundsystem discography}}\n* ''[[LCD Soundsystem (album)|LCD Soundsystem]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Sound of Silver]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[This Is Happening]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[American Dream (LCD Soundsystem album)|American Dream]]'' (2017)\n\n=== With Falling Man ===\n* ''A Christening'' (1988)\n\n=== With Pony ===\n* ''Cosmovalidator'' (1994)\n\n=== With Speedking ===\n* ''The Fist and the Laurels'' (2002)\n\n=== Solo ===\n* ''Remixes Made with Tennis Data'' (2014)\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|James Murphy (electronic musician)}}\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.npr.org/2010/06/21/127745800/james-murphy-the-man-behind-lcd-soundsystem In-depth radio interview] with James Murphy on ''[[Fresh Air]]'' (38 mins; 2010)\n\n{{LCD Soundsystem}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murphy, James}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American DJs]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Remixers]]\n[[Category:LCD Soundsystem members]]\n[[Category:Singers from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from West Windsor Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:West Windsor-Plainsboro High School South alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Koavf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Murphy_(electronic_musician)"}
